description: View of the right atrial appendage.  The pectinate muscles are shown as well as the very thin membranous region between.  The crista terminalis is the upside down "U-shaped" structure at the top of the screen.

In this image, the camera is sitting in the right atrial chamber and pointing slightly upward in order to view the inside of the appendage. Pectinate muscles can be seen in the lower left hand corner, while the light colored areas in the distance are the appendage wall.  The crista terminalis is seen traversing the upper right corner of the screen, while the sagittal band travels from the upper left corner of the image through the middle of the image.
View of the right atrial free wall.  The pectinate muscles can be seen as well as the very thin membranous regions between.  The right atrial appendage is off the screen to the upper left.
View of the right atrial appendage showing the pectinate muscles and the very thin membranous regions in between.  A Medtronic business card can clearly be read through the wall.

View of the central portion of the crista terminalis as well as the anterior portion of the right atrial free wall.  The atrial appendage is off the screen to the upper left.  Pectinate muscles can be seen, as well as the very thin membranous regions between.

View of the anterior free wall of the right atrium.  The crista terminalis can be seen at the very top of the screen.  The right atrial appendage is located to the left and upper left of the screen and continues off the screen.

Rotated view of the RAA, with the top of the image being the anterior aspect of the RAA. In this view, the sagittal band is the large structure in the middle of the screen.  The crista terminalis is off the screen on the right hand side.

In this image, the camera is sitting in the right atrial chamber and pointing slightly upward in order to view the inside of the appendage. In this image, the sagittal band travels from the upper left hand corner to the center of the RAA.  The RAA freewall is on the right and the crista terminalis is above this image, travelling parallel to the free wall and perpindicular to the sagittal band.
Atrial fibrillation can be seen on the appendage wall.  Crista terminalis on the upper right, fibrillation observed in the pectinate muscles on the left.
Atrial fibrillation in RA appendage; crista terminalis on upper right.
Atrial fibrillation in RA appendage pectinate muscles; note how thin walled the RA is between pectinate muscles.

Right atrial appendage is backlit in contracting heart; backlit is turned off during the clip. The tricuspid valve is to the left of the screen; note how thin walled the RA is between pectinate muscles.
Contracting right atrial appendage; note how thin walled the RA is between pectinate muscles; text on Dr. Iaizzo’s business card can be read through the wall.
Contracting right atrial appendage, but noted flutter in pectinate muscles.
Right atrial appendage and sagittal band. Sagittal band seen in the center of the screen.
View of the right atrial appendage - the pectinate muscles alternate with thin walls. The crista terminalis is just off the top of the screen.
View of right atrial appendage wall with pectinate muscles.  Septomarginal trabeculations can be seen to the left of the view.
View of right atrial appendage with pectinate muscles; anterior of heart is to the left.
View of the right atrial appendage.
View of the right atrial appendage with a close-up of the crista terminalis.
View of the right atrial appendage from inside the right atrium during the onset of atrial fibrillation, characterized by a wave motion.
Close up view of the right atrial appendage showing the pectinate muscles.

The extremely thin walls of the right atrium are demonstrated in this clip of a business card seen through the appendage.  This anatomical phenomenon exemplifies the caution required when placing active fixation leads in the appendage.

The right atrial appendage can be seen displaying the pectinate muscles and the start of the crista terminalis, to the top right of the image.  The quivering of the appendage is most probably due to the fact that the reanimated heart is not supported externally, as by the pericardium in the body.
View of the right atrial appendage showing the pectinate muscles of the endocardial surface.  The tricuspid valve can be seen to the bottom left and the crista terminalis to the upper right.
The right atrial appendage with pectinate muscle.
The right atrial appendage is seen with light from the exterior of the heart shining through it's thin epicardium. Trebeculations are also prominent within the appendage.

The right atrial appendage is seen with the free wall on the right side of the video. External light can be seen though the free wall in between the trebeculae due to its thin and semi-translucent nature of the atrium.

In this image, the camera is sitting in the right atrial chamber and pointing slightly upward in order to view the inside of the appendage.  View of the RAA with many trabeculations present.  Crista terminalis travels along the tops of the screen.
Looking towards the RAA freewall, with the crista terminalis in the upper right hand corner.
Rotated view of the RAA, the top of the image being the posterior aspect of the RAA and the left of the image being the crista terminalis.

Rotated view of the RAA, the bottom of the image being the crista terminalis.  Excellent example of networked pectinate muscles forming a trabeculated surface very similar in appearance to the ventricles.
View into the right atrial appendage/auricle. Excellent example of networked pectinate muscles forming a trabeculated surface very similar in appearance to the ventricles.

In this image, the camera is sitting in the right atrial chamber and pointing slightly upward in order to view the inside of the appendage. Crista terminalis travelling along the upper right portion of the image, with the sagittal band traversing down the RAA in the distance.
View into the right atrial appendage/auricle. Excellent example of networked pectinate muscles forming a trabeculated surface very similar in appearance to the ventricles.
Rotated view of the RAA, the top of the image being the posterior aspect of the RAA and the left of the image being the crista terminalis.

In this image, the camera is sitting in the right atrial chamber and pointing slightly upward in order to view the inside of the appendage. Crista terminalis travelling along the upper right portion of the image, with the sagittal band traversing down the RAA in the distance.

In this image, the camera is sitting in the right atrial chamber and pointing slightly upward in order to view the inside of the appendage. Crista terminalis travelling along the left edge of the image, with the sagittal band traversing from the left to the middle of the image.
Upclose view of an unique pectinate muscle in the right atrial appendage.
A right margin view of a heart in which the pericardium was removed.
Camera starts inside coronary sinus and then backs out to show coronary sinus ostium partially covered by a small crescent Thebesian valve.
View of the coronary sinus ostium and Thebesian valve.  The anatomy of this region is a little distorted due to the placement of the cannula in the inferior vena cava.

View of the coronary sinus ostium and Thebesian valve.  The camera advances towards the ostium showing the proximal portion of the coronary sinus.  A small venous valve can be seen opening and closing at the bottom of the coronary sinus.
View of the coronary sinus ostium and Thebesian valve.  The camera is facing towards the lateral/posterior wall of the right atrium looking into the very small ostium.
View of the coronary sinus ostium and Thebesian valve.  The camera is facing towards the tricuspid valve and shows the movement of the fenestrated Thebesian valve during the cardiac cycle.
Close-up view of the lumen of the coronary sinus.   Many small venous openings can be seen as the camera is retracted back into the right atrium.
A close up view of the coronary sinus.  At the end of the video clip, the ostium for the venous return from the posterior interventricular vein can be seen at the bottom right of the image.

View of the coronary sinus ostium and Thebesian valve.  The camera advances towards the ostium showing the proximal portion of the coronary sinus.  A small venous valve can be seen opening and closing at the bottom of the coronary sinus.
View of the coronary sinus.  The camera advances into the coronary sinus showing small cardiac venous ostia within.
View of the inside of the coronary sinus at the very distal end.  Shown is the great cardiac vein and the oblique vein of the left atrium, as well as the valve of Vieussens.
Close-up view of the valve of Vieussens and another small venous valve at the distal end of the coronary sinus.
View of Valve of Vieussens (and of Great Cardiac Vein) within the coronary sinus.

View of the coronary sinus ostium and Thebesian valve.  The valve is fenestrated with a few larger openings.  The Eustachian ridge can be seen starting from the center of the screen to the upper left corner.
View of a coronary venous ostium inside the coronary sinus.  A venous valve can be seen partially occluding the ostium.
View of the coronary sinus ostium.  The Thebesian valve was ripped during explant.  Sutures closing the inferior vena cava ostium can be seen at the top of the screen.
RA is fibrillating. The coronary sinus ostium is in the middle of the screen covered by a fairly prominent Thebesian valve; tricuspid valve is to the right.
Coronary sinus ostium partially covered with Thebesian valve; several small venous ostia can be seen just inside in the coronary sinus

Close-up of a coronary sinus ostium, covered by a  crescent shaped Thebesian valve. The tricuspid valve is to the right bottom corner of the screen; a Millar® pressure transducer is going through the valve.  The heart is fibrillating.
View just inside the coronary sinus; coronary venous ostia are visible at the top and bottom of the sinus.
Coronary sinus and very large Thebesian valve that covers the majority of the ostium; the tricuspid valve is to the right bottom screen.
A direct view into the coronary sinus ostium. Note the  small Thebesian valve and a flailing band above the ostium.
Coronary sinus ostium; a relatively small Thebesian valve connected to fibrous banding can be seen at the bottom of the ostium. Note a flailing band above the ostium.
The coronary sinus ostium is covered by a large Thebesian valve. The posterior portion of the tricuspid valve can be seen in the lower right of the screen.
Close-up view of the coronary sinus ostium. A Thebesian vein ostium can also be seen to the right of the screen.
The coronary sinus ostium is partially covered with a Thebesian valve. The IVC cannula can be seen at the top of the screen. Pectinate muscles of the RA can be seen to the left of the screen.
View of the coronary sinus ostium.  A Thebesian valve is partially obstructing the opening.
View of the coronary sinus ostium.  A thin Thebesian valve is partially obstructing the opening.

View of the main venous return Â of the heart, the coronary sinus ostium, from the right atrium. A Thebesian valve is partially obstructing the opening. Thebesian valves can cause difficulties for physicians trying to gain left sided access from the right side of the heart via the coronary veins.
Inside the coronary sinus; many branches and ridges are visible.

View of the coronary sinus sostium partially covered by the Thebesian valve.Â Thebesian valves can cause difficulties for physicians trying to gain left sided access from the right side of the heart via the coronary veins.

View of the coronary sinus ostium showing the remnants of the thebesian valve.  The IVC is to the upper left of the image and the pectinate muscles of the Right atrial appendage can be seen to the lower left.
Close up view of the coronary sinus ostium with the thebesian valve remnants on the right of the image.
Inside the coronary sinus highlighting the varied anatomy of the coronary venous system.

Coronary sinus ostium. The pectinate muscles of the right atrial endocardial wall can be seen to the left.  The branching of the coronary vasculature can be seen within the ostium and the thebesian valve can be seen around the left hand edge.
View inside the coronary sinus. The thebesian valve can be seen to the left and a separate ostium to the posterior ventricular vein can be seen to the right of the coronary sinus.
The coronary ostium is viewed from the right atrium.  A rudimentary thebesian valve is present.  The shot starts zoomed into the ostium and pans outwards.
View of the coronary sinus ostium while the heart is fibrillating.  The Thebesian valve can be seen to cover the vast majority if the coronary sinus ostium.
A view from just inside the coronary sinus, with the Thebesian valve visible on the left.
A close up shot of the coronary sinus ostium with Thebesian valve.

The coronary sinus osteium is seen from the right atrium with a thebesian valve partially covering the opening. As the samera slightly moves down the annulus of the tricuspid valve comes into view in the bottom corner of the screen.

View of the coronary sinus ostium and Thebesian valve.  The tricuspid valve is located to the lower right of the image, off the screen, and the superior vena cava is located off the top of the screen.  The coronary sinus is compressed just passed the ostium.

When viewing the coronary sinus os, the camera sits in the RA chamber, pointing septally, just superior to the tricuspid valve. The coronary sinus os can be seen in the middle of the screen, with the Thebesian valve seen covering the left portion of the os. Zooming out toward the end of the clip  provides a reference with respect to the tricuspid valve.

When viewing the coronary sinus os, the camera sits in the RA chamber, pointing septally, just superior to the tricuspid valve. Another view of the Thebesian Valve covering the entire left portion of the CS os- in this view, the thin nature of the valve can be seen.

In this image, the camera is sitting just above the tricuspid valve and pointing posteriorly, down the coronary sinus. CS os with Thebesian valve.  The base of the heart is located toward the right portion of the screen, whereas the apex is toward the left.
In this image, the camera is sitting just above the tricuspid valve and pointing posteriorly, down the coronary sinus. Rotating view of CS os and Thebesian valve, in the physiologic orientation.

In this image, the camera is sitting just above the tricuspid valve and pointing postero-septally, toward the coronary sinus. Entire CS os can be seen through the thin Thebesian valve, which covers approximately 40% of the os.
In this image, the camera is sitting just above the tricuspid valve and pointing postero-septally, toward the coronary sinus.  Another view of os and valve from heart #16.

In this image, the camera is sitting just above the tricuspid valve and pointing septally, toward the coronary sinus.The ridges seen in the middle of this image are along the wall of the CS, which travels behind the ridges.  A Thebesian valve can be made out toward the upper right hand portion of the ridgeline, where the CS os can be found.

Perfusion fixed heart.  View of the coronary sinus ostium and a prominent Thebesian valve.  The camera pans from a more global view to one looking down the coronary sinus.  The tricuspid valve can be seen to the lower right of the screen.  The inferior vena cava and Eustachian ridge can be seen to the upper left.
Another view of the os and valve from heart #18, this time, peering down the os, with the Thebesian valve being the thin membrane on the left.
Camera positioned above the tricuspid valve, tilted slightly anteriorly.  Coronary sinus covered by Thebesian valve.
Another view of the os and valve from heart #19, with camera pointing in aposterior direction.  Valve appears partially collasped in this view.
Camera positioned above the tricuspid valve, tilted slightly anteriorly.  Weblike structure is the Thebesian valve covering the CS os.
Another view of the Thebesian valve from heart #22 seen in the lower right portion of the image.
Camera positioned above the tricuspid valve, tilted slightly anteriorly. Very slight weblike Thebesian valve, covering approximately less than 10% of the CS os.

View looking straight at the coronary sinus, with the Thebesian valve framing the os of the sinus.Â Thebesian valves can cause difficulties for physicians trying to gain left sided access from the right side of the heart via the coronary veins.
Lateral crista terminalis is shown, then camera moves to show tricuspid valve and lateral wall.
View of the crista terminalis in the right atrium.  The camera pans from the lateral aspect to the septal aspect with the free wall of the right atrium visible in the background.

View of the right atrial appendage in the background.  In the foreground is the septal aspect of the crista terminals.  The large pectinate muscle arising from the crista terminalis is the taenia sagittalis.  The camera then pans to follow the crista terminalis to the lateral aspect, near the inferior vena cava ostium.  The free wall of the right atrium can be seen as well.
View of the septal aspect of the crista terminalis.  The free wall can be seen in the background as well as the tricuspid valve in the very bottom of the screen.
View of the crista terminalis in the right atrium.  The camera pans from the septal aspect to the lateral aspect with the free wall of the right atrium visible in the background.
A panning shot of the crista terminalis with the tricuspid valve in the background at the beginning and then the right atrial appendage.
A panning shot of the crista terminalis with the right atrial appendage in the background.
The camera pans across the crista terminalis, starting with the lateral aspect and going towards the anterior of the heart.
Panning view of crista terminalis with a view of the right atrial appendage in the background.
A close up view of pectinate muscle, at the end of the clip the camera pans upward and the crista terminalis can be seen.
View fo the crista terminalis in the right atrium. Â The crista terminalis is on the far right in the image and the tricuspid valve annulus can be seen in the bottom left.
The crista terminalis is viewed with the pectinate muscle in the background.  The shot sweeps medially to view where the crista terminalis meets the interatrial wall.

The crista terminalis can be seen in the upper foreground of this footage as the camera pans along the structure.  The right atrium can be seen in the background exhibiting the pectinate muscles of the epicardial surface.
From within the right atrium the christa terminalis is seen arching next to the free wall of the right atrium.
Perfusion fixed heart.  Camera pans from lateral aspect of crista terminals to septal aspect.  The free wall of the right atrium can be seen in the background.
Camera pointing toward the top of the appendage. Crista terminalis is lit up in the foreground of the image, while the trabeculations on the wall of the RAA can be seen in the background.
Camera pointing toward the free wall of the appendage. Crista terminalis is lit up in the foreground of the image, while the trabeculations on the wall of the RAA can be seen in the background.

End portion of crista terminalis seen here when intersecting with the RAA wall. Â The crista terminalis is surrounded byÂ pectinate muscle (musculi pectinati) and is generally described as looking like the teeth of a comb.
Perfusion fixed heart.  View of the crista terminalis.  The camera pans from the septal aspect to the lateral aspect.  The appendage and free wall of the right atrium can be seen in the back.
Camera sitting in RA, pointing into the appendage. Crista terminalis seen in the upper right portion of the image.

Good view of arching crista terminalis defining the opening for the RAA.  Below the arch the pectinate muscle (musculi pectinati) can be seen.  This muscle is generally described as looking like the teeth of a comb.
Good view of arching crista terminalis defining the opening for the RAA.
Crista terminalis framing the upper portion of the image, with the RAA seen in the background.

Perfusion fixed heart.  View of the crista terminalis in the right atrium.  The camera pans from the septal aspect to the lateral aspect with the free wall of the right atrium visible in the background.
Camera is within the RAA, with a view of the termination of crista terminalis along the RAA wall.

View of crista terminalis arching over the opening for the RAA. In the lower right portion the pectinate muscle (musculi pectinati) can be seen.  This muscle is generally described as looking like the teeth of a comb, but these have a non-normal appearance.

Perfusion fixed heart.  View of the crista terminalis in the right atrium.  The camera pans from the septal aspect to the lateral aspect with the free wall of the right atrium visible in the background.

Camera is sitting in the right atrium, pointing toward the opening for the RAA.  The crista terminalis forms a perfect arch along the outline of the RAA.  Trabeculations can be seen in the wall of the RAA.
Same view as from Heart 022-1, only lit to accentuate the crista terminalis.
Crista terminalis forms a perfect arch along the outline of the RAA.  Trabeculations can be seen in the wall of the RAA.

View of the fossa ovalis from the right atrium.  The fossa ovalis is illuminated from a light source in the left atrium.  Halfway though the clip, the backlighting is turned off for a few seconds and then turned on again.
View of the atrial septum from the right side.  The fossa ovalis is illuminated through the septum from a light source in the left atrium.

View of the atrial septum from the right side.  The fossa ovalis is illuminated through the septum from a light source in the left atrium for the beginning of the clip and is illuminated from the right atrium towards the end of the clip.

View of the atrial septum from the right side.  The fossa ovalis is seen in the center of the screen, with the inferior vena cava cannula to the left of the image.  The superior limbus can be seen clearly at the top of the fossa ovalis.  A faint backlight from a light source in the left atrium can be seen about half-way through the clip.
A full view of the Fossa ovalis; note that a Millar® pressure transducer in the left atrium can be seen through the thin septal tissue.  To the left of the Fossa is an implanted IVC cannula.

The Thebesian valve (straight on view) can be seen contracting in front of the coronary sinus ostium (to the right of the screen).  A suture for securing the cannula into the IVC can been seen in the upper left corner.
The fossa ovalis it is located just above the coronary sinus (to the lower left). To the far lower left of the screen is the inferior vena cava cannula.
View of the interatrial septum with the fossa ovalis to the left side of the screen.
View of the fossa ovalis from the right atrium.
View of the fossa ovalis from the right atrium.  The heart has an atrial septal defect in the form of a patent forman ovalis that can be seen on the right side of the fossa.
Close up view of the patent forman ovali in the septal wall of the atrium.

The fossa ovalis viewed from the right atrium during sinus rhythm demonstrating the flexibility of the tissue.  A slight patency to the anatomical feature can be seen in the upper right corner of the image.
The fossa ovalis is seen in the right atrium in relation to the inferior vena cava, then close up.
The thin fossa ovalis is shown here as seen from the right atrium.

The fossa ovalis is seen in the video as it pans to the superior portion of the fossa and returns back to the inferior portion of the fossa. This particular heart also has an almost hidden patent foramen ovale (PFO). The opening of this defect can be seen at the bottom right of the fossa as a darkened sulcus which extends to the right behind the other septal tissue. No flow was observed while the heart was functioning, however cardiac instruments were able to traverse this particular defect.

This image shows a close up of this heart with a patent foramen ovale (PFO). The top indentation seen is the origin of the PFO from the right atrium. The camera then begins to zoom out and the motion of the fossa due to the pressure differences in the cardiac cycle is clearly illustrated here.
Fossa ovalis, backlit from the LAA
View of the fossa ovalis in the right atrium.  A Millar® pressure transducer catheter is passing through the patent foramen ovale from the left atrium to the right atrium.

View of the atrial septum from the right side.  The fossa ovalis is in the center of the screen.  There is a large pressure differential between the left atrium and the right atrium, causing the fossa ovalis to bulge into the right atrium during contraction.
Fossa ovalis can be seen to the right of the screen, next to the IVC cannula.
View of fossa ovalis; PFO is present on the left side.

A patent foramen ovale (PFO) in the atrial septal wall can be seen at the top right of the screen with the IVC cannula to the far left.  The large dilation of the atrial septal wall indicates how thin the structure is.
The fossa ovalis is viewed from the right atrium.

When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  Fossa ovalis seen from a distance: the semicircular curve that looks like a backwards "C" frames the fossa ovalis.

When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  The fossa ovalis seen up close, the flat tissue in the shape of an oval is the fossa ovalis.
When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  The fossa ovalis is backlit from the left atrium.
When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  The fossa ovalis is backlit from the left atrium.
When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  The fossa ovalis is backlit from the left atrium.
When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  The fossa ovalis is backlit from the left atrium.
When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  The fossa ovalis is backlit from the left atrium.
When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  The fossa ovalis is backlit from the left atrium-BRIGHT.
When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  The fossa ovalis is backlit from the left atrium.
Fossa ovalis seen in the upper middle portion of the image- it takes on a circular shape.
Fossa ovalis seen in the middle portion of the image- it takes on a circular shape.

When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  Fossa ovalis is backlit from the left atrium and is seen in the middle portion of the image.
When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  Almond shaped fossa ovalis in middle of image.
When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  Almond shaped fossa ovalis in middle of image, backlit.
When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  Almond shaped fossa ovalis in middle of image, backlit, and upclose.
When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  Almond shaped fossa ovalis in middle of image, dimly backlit, and upclose.
When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  Fossa ovalis seen in the center of the image.
When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  Fossa ovalis seen in the center of the image, backlit brightly.
When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  Fossa ovalis seen in the center of the image, backlit dimly.

When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  Fossa ovalis lit from the right atrium.  This structure is more difficult to recognize when not backlit.
When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  A membranous, thick fossa ovalis.
When viewing the fossa ovalis from the right atrium, the camera sits in the chamber and points toward the mid-septal wall.  A membranous, thick fossa ovalis, backlit.

View  of the atrial septum from the right side.  The coronary sinus ostium is in the lower right corner, the inferior vena cava cannula in the upper left, and the Eustachian ridge spanning between the two.  A remnant Thebesian valve can also be seen partially covering the coronary sinus ostium.
Inferior vena cava opening with sewn in cannula.  The fossa ovalis can be seen transiently on the right of the frame and the camera pans to include the tricuspid valve.
IVC cannula in right atrium.
View of cannulated inferior vena cava ostium.
View of cannulated inferior vena cava ostium.
The camera is pointed in a posterior-inferior directions to view the IVC os seen in this image, tied off for functional use on the Visible Heart® Apparatus
The camera is pointed in a posterior-inferior directions to view the IVC os seen in this image, tied off for functional use on the Visible Heart® Apparatus
The camera is pointed in a posterior-inferior directions to view the IVC os seen in this image, tied off for functional use on the Visible Heart® Apparatus
IVC os on left side of image, tied off.  The ridge in the middle of the image separates the IVC os from the tricuspid valve.
IVC tied off from outside the heart
Seen in this image is the interatrial septum, which divides the left and right atria.
Interatrial septum; the coronary sinus ostium is to the left of the screen and the tricuspid valve is to the right; this is the region of the Triangle of Koch.
Right atrial septal wall; the camera pans to show the tricuspid valve to the right of the screen near the end of the clip.
Bachmann’s Bundle area; the tricuspid valve is to the lower right of the screen.
View of interatrial septum; mitral valve can be seen in the bottom right corner.
The right atrial septal wall.  The large dilation of the wall during atrial contraction helps to show the pressure differences between the right and left atria.
The thin septal wall between the atria, known as the fossa ovalis, can be seen bulging into the right atria.  This phenomenon is due to the higher pressures on the left side of the heart.

High septum of the right atrium between the fossa ovalis on the left, the right auricle on the right and the tricuspid valve below.  This area is considered important in atrial pacing due to its proximity to the sinoatrial node.
Low portion of the interatrial septum seen in this image, with the IVC os seen in the upper left corner of the image and the tricuspid valve seen in the lower right corner of the image.
High portion of the interatrial septum seen in this image, with the fossa ovalis seen in the lower left corner of the image.
Low portion of the interatrial septum seen in this image, the fossa ovalis can be seen near the upper right corner of the image.
High portion of the interatrial septum seen here with venous return ostium in the middle of the image.
High portion of the interatrial septum seen here, the fossa ovalis can be seen as the darker, circular structure left of the center of the image.
Fossa ovalis is dark, circular structure near the center of the image.  The IVC os can be seen in the lower left corner of the image, while the tricuspid valve is in the lower right corner.
Image of the high portion of the interatrial septum, with the tricuspid valve in the bottom right corner, and fossa ovalis to the left.

In the bottom left corner the fossa ovalis can be seen and below that, out of the image, is the opening of the inferior vena cava. To the right of the fossa ovalis is the Eustachian valve and traveling up from the Eustachian valve is the tendon of Todaro. To the right of the Eustachian valve is the coronary sinus ostium and to the right of the ostium is the tricuspid valve in the bottom right corner.
High portion of the interatrial septum seen in this image.

Good view of multiple structures along with the interatrial septum.  In the lower left portion of the image, the IVC os is seen, tied off, where as on the lower right portion of the image, the tricuspid valve is seen, with the coronary sinus os between the two.
High portion of the interatrial septum seen in this image
Interatrial septum seen in the upper portion of the image.  The tricuspid valve is seen in the lower right corner.
High portion of the interatrial septum seen in this image.
Interatrial septum covers the upper half of the image, the tricuspid valve can be seen in the lower right portion of the image.

The lateral wall can be seen fibrillating in this footage; some residual air bubbles from the reanimation process are present. The pectinate muscle (musculi pectinati) can be clearly seen with thin regions visible between the muscular ridges. This muscle is generally described as looking like the teeth of a comb.

The lateral wall can be seen fibrillating in a more coordinated fashion in this clip.  This is often a result of the rewarming process as the myocardial tissue changes from the initial uncoordinated contractions.

Lateral wall fibrillation; tricuspid valve is to the left of the screen and the body of a pacing lead can be seen in the upper left corner. The footage shows the atrial wall contracting out of sync with the paced ventricle, as evidenced by the function of the tricuspid valve, indicating that the heart is not generating a native sinus rhythm.
The anterior region of the right atrial lateral wall; the crista terminalis can be seen at the top of the screen. Note how thin walled the RA is between pectinate muscles.

Close up view of the lateral wall of the right atrium. . The pectinate muscle (musculi pectinati) can be seen clearly. This muscle is generally described as looking like the teeth of a comb. Note how thin walled the atrial wall is between pectinate muscles.

View of the lateral wall of the right atrium. Pectinate muscles can be seen spanning the entire region. The coronary sinus ostium can be seen late in the clip near the upper right corner. The inferior vena cava cannula is just off the top of the screen.

Footage of the superior region of the right atrial lateral wall taken with a camera pointing in a superior-posterior direction. The pectinate muscles of the lateral wall can be seen traveling vertically, along surface of the wall. The superior vena cava cannula can be seen in the upper right portion of the image.

Up close view of pectinate muscles (musculi pectinati) coursing across the endocardial surface of the lateral wall. This muscle is generally described as looking like the teeth of a comb. Note how thin walled the RA is between pectinate muscles.

Camera is positioned to view the anterior lateral aspect of the lateral wall, often labeled the free wall. This image, taken from inside the right atrium, demonstrates the extremely thin nature of the wall by viewing a ruler on the exterior of the heart.

Lateral wall of the right atrium; the tricuspid valve can be seen to the left of the screen. The end of the footage is an excellent example of how thin the lateral wall can be, evidenced by the darker "windows" between the pectinate muscles.
The lateral wall of the right atrium covered in pectinate muscles; the crista terminalis can be seen in the upper right corner.

Up close view of pectinate muscles (musculi pectinati) travelling along the endocardial surface of the right atrial lateral wall. This muscle is generally described as looking like the teeth of a comb.

Close-up of the inferior portion of the right atrial lateral wall; pectinate muscles of the appendage can be seen in the background with the tricuspid vale to the lower left. A mapping electrode catheter is threaded into the right atrial appendage. The footage ends with a shot of the inferior vena cava cannula.
The lateral wall is viewed with a side-view camera entering the right atrium through the superior vena cava.
Right atrial lateral wall; pectinate muscles of the anterior aspect of the wall can be seen in the background with the crista terminalis in the upper right.

Camera is positioned to view the lateral wall of the right atrium. The anterior region of the right atrium can be seen in the left portion of this image, evident by the pectinate muscle traveling along the wall. In the center of the image is the ridge which separates the free wall from the septal wall, which is seen in the right portion of the image.

Camera is positioned to view the anterior lateral aspect of the lateral wall. The lateral wall of this heart is highly trabeculated. The V-shaped structure at the top of the screen is the beginning of the crista terminalis, which will travel along the roof of the RA, separating the RA appendage from the rest of the chamber.
The anterior portion of the right atrial lateral wall can be seen I this image.  The crista terminalis can be seen to the upper right of the image.

Camera pointing in an inferior-posterior direction to view a portion of the lateral wall of the right atrium. The inferior vena cava is tied off in the upper right portion of this image, with the right atrial lateral wall seen in the surrounding area. The V-shaped structure at the top of the screen is the beginning of the crista terminalis, which will travel along the roof of the RA, separating the RA appendage from the rest of the chamber.

Lateral wall of the right atrium, pectinate muscles can be seen traveling in many directions along surface of the wall. The back lit tissue exemplifies the thin lateral wall tissue between the ridges of the pectinate muscle.
Seen in this image are the pectinate muscles branching and traveling along the surface of the right atrial lateral wall. The start of the crista terminalis can be seen in the lower left of the image.

Full view of right atrial chamber, with the lateral wall seen on the left, the septum on the right and the inferior vena cava with a prominent Eustachian valve near the top of the image (round, dark-colored shape).
Good example of branching of the pectinate muscles which cover the interior surface of the right atrial lateral wall.

View of the coronary sinus ostium and Thebesian valve while the right atrium is fibrillating.  The tricuspid valve can be seen to the lower right.  The triangle of Koch is in the center of the screen.
View of the triangle of Koch.  The coronary sinus and a remnant Thebesian valve are shown in the upper left.  The tricuspid valve is located to the lower right.
Triangle of Koch seen from a distance.  The coronary sinus ostium and tricuspid valve can also be seen.

View of the triangle of Koch.  The coronary sinus ostium and a remnant Thebesian valve can be seen on the left border of the image.  The tricuspid valve is located in the center and central bottom of the clip; the septal leaflet is located centrally and the anterior leaflet towards the lower right corner.  The Eustachian ridge can also be seen leaving the superior border of the coronary sinus ostium and heading towards the upper left.

View of the triangle of Koch.  The coronary sinus ostium can be seen on the left side of the clip and the tricuspid valve to the center and lower right.  The septal leaflet is to the center of the image and the anterior leaflet to the lower right.
View of the triangle of Koch. The coronary sinus is shown in the lower left. The tricuspid valve is located to the lower right.

To view the tricuspid valve in the RA, the camera enters through the superior vena cava and points apically.  This example of the tricuspid valve actually has four leaflets, which is not very unusual.  The coronary sinus is seen on the right edge of the image, partially obstructed by a Thebesian valve.  The septal leaflet is on the upper left portion of the valve, and with the coronary sinus os, creates border regions of the tiangle of Koch.
Triangle of Koch; coronary sinus ostium is to the left of the screen and the tricuspid valve is to the right.

Triangle of Koch - coronary sinus ostium is to the top left of the screen, a Thebesian valve ostium is to the top right of the screen. A portion of a tricuspid valve leaflet is in the bottom right corner of the screen.
Triangle of Koch - the coronary sinus ostium is to the left of the screen and the tricuspid valve is to the right.
Close-up view of the triangle of Koch. The tricuspid valve is to the bottom right of the screen and the coronary sinus ostium (with a large Thebesian valve) can be seen to the left of the screen.
View of the triangle of Koch with the coronary sinus ostium in the lower left and the septal leaflet of the mitral valve on the right.
View of the Triangle of Koch; CS is seen on the bottom left and the tricuspid valve is present on the right.

View of the triangle of Koch. The tricuspid valve is to the bottom right of the screen and the coronary sinus ostium (with the remnants of a thebesian valve) can be seen to the left of the screen.  The pectinate muscles of the right atrial appendage can be seen at the bottom left of the screen.
The triangle of Koch can be shown, with the coronary sinus on the left and the tricuspid valve on the right.
Coronary sinus partially obstructed by a Thebesian valve is seen on the left of this image.  The septal leaflet of the tricuspid valve is in view, with the triangle of Koch between these structures.
Coronary sinus is seen to the left of center in this image.  The septal leaflet of the tricuspid valve is in view, with the triangle of Koch between these structures, in the center of the image.

To view the tricuspid valve in the RA, the camera enters through the superior vena cava and points apically.  Seen in this image is the tricuspid valvein the center of the image.  The coronary sinus is just to the left of the valve (appearing rather flat) and the fleshy portion between these structures in the triangle of Koch.

Coronary sinus partially obstructed by a Thebesian valve is seen on the far left of this image.  The septal leaflet of the tricuspid valve is in view, with the triangle of Koch between these structures, in the center of the image.

Coronary sinus obstructed by a rather large Thebesian valve is seen on the left of this image.  The septal and anterior leaflets of the tricuspid valve are in view (anterior leaflet on the right edge of the valve), with the triangle of Koch between the septal leaflet and coronary sinus.

Triangle of Koch sits in the middle of the image.  The coronary sinus has a very circular shape to it and borders one edge of the triangle, while the septal leaflet of the tricuspid valve makes up another border of this structure.

The triangle of Koch is located between the coronary sinus os (small circular opening near the center of the image) and the tricuspid valve’s septal leaflet (leaflet on the furthest left portion of the valve).

The coronary sinus, which makes up a border of the triangle of Koch is difficult to make out in this image, as it’s concealed by a Thebesian valve.  Another border of the triangle of Koch is the septal leaflet of the tricuspid valve (seen in the center of the image).
Tricuspid valve viewed from the right atrium.  Anterior leaflet to the lower right, posterior leaflet to the lower left, and septal leaflet to the top.

View of the tricuspid valve from the right atrium.  The septal leaflet is to the left, the anterior leaflet to the upper right, and the posterior to the lower right.  A pacing lead can be seen passing through the valve.

Close-up view of the tricuspid valve from the right atrium.  The septal leaflet is to the upper left, the anterior leaflet to the upper right, and the posterior leaflet to the bottom right.  The anterior papillary muscle can be seen in the right ventricle  between the anterior and posterior leaflets when the valve is open.

View of the tricuspid valve from the right atrium, backlit from the right ventricle.  The septal leaflet is to the left, the anterior leaflet to the upper right, and the posterior to the lower right.  The Thebesian valve can just be seen on the left of the image.

View of the tricuspid valve from the right atrium.  The septal leaflet is to the upper right, the anterior leaflet to the lower right/bottom, and the posterior leaflet to the left.  The head of the anterior papillary muscle can be seen in the center of the screen when the valve is open.

View of the triangle of Koch.  The membranous septum is illuminated by a light source placed in the left ventricle.  The coronary sinus ostium can be seen on the left of the image and the tricuspid valve to the lower right.

View of the tricuspid valve from the right atrium.  The septal leaflet is to the left, the anterior leaflet to the right, and the posterior leaflet to the bottom.   Pectinate muscles on the free wall can be seen on the right and lower right of the image.

To view the tricuspid valve in the RA, the camera enters through the superior vena cava and points apically.  View of the tricuspid valve from the RA. The largest of the three leaflets is seen in the lower corner of the image, where it spans the length of the valve.  The other two leaflets are about 1/2 of the length of the largest leaflet to which they are opposite of, near the center of the image.  The thin white string-like structures seen through the valve, in the right ventricle, are the chordae tendinae, which attach to the papillary muscles and prevent the valve leaflets from prolapsing.

To view the tricuspid valve in the RA, the camera enters through the superior vena cava and points apically. The largest of the three leaflets is seen on the left side of the valve, where it spans the length of the valve.  The thin white string-like structures seen through the valve, in the right ventricle, are the chordae tendinae, which attach to the papillary muscles and prevent the valve leaflets from prolapsing.

To view the tricuspid valve in the RA, the camera enters through the superior vena cava and points apically.  This example of the tricuspid valve actually has four leaflets, which is not very unusual.  The coronary sinus is seen on the right edge of the image, partially obstructed by a Thebesian valve.  The septal leaflet is on the upper left portion of the valve, and with the coronary sinus os, creates border regions of the tiangle of Koch.
Tricuspid valve, seen from right atrium; in this case the heart is functioning somewhat poorly.
The tricuspid valve seen from the right atrium, chordae tendinae seen through valve; in this case the heart is functioning somewhat poorly.
Tricuspid valve seen from right atrium; valve is functioning well and closing completely.
Close-up of tricuspid valve; valve is functioning somewhat well.
View of smaller posterior leaflets of tricuspid valve.

Tricuspid valve, looking inferior from the right atrium. Through the valve the apex of the right ventricle can be seen and the trabeculated muscle network with chordae tendinae attaching to papillary muscles.

View of the tricuspid valve from the superior vena cava ostium. This valve has 4 distinguishable leaflets. The right atrial appendage is to the right of the screen. The posterior leaflet is to the lower left, the septal leaflet is to the upper left and the anterior leaflet is to the top of the valve; another leaflet is distinguishable to the lower right.
View of tricuspid valve from right atrium with brief glimpse of chordae tendinae.
View of tricuspid valve from right atrium with brief glimpse of chordae tendinae.
View of tricuspid valve from right atrium with an excellent example of networked chordae tendinae in the valve commissures between individual valve leaflet scallops (regions).

View of the tricuspid valve from the right atrium. The valve is functioning well with good leaflet coaptation.  The chordae tendinae of the anterior papillary muscle can be seen through the valve during diastole.
The tricuspid valve is shown from the right atrium, with the camera entering through the superior vena cava.
The tricuspid valve is viewed from the right atrium. The image zooms in on the valve and the trebeculations of the right ventricular apex can be seen through the opening of the valve.
Tricuspid valve before and after defibrillating shock.

To view the tricuspid valve in the RA, the camera enters through the superior vena cava and points apically.  Seen in this image is the tricuspid valve in the center of the image.  The coronary sinus is just to the left of the valve and the fleshy portion between these structures in the triangle of Koch.
To view the tricuspid valve in the RA, the camera enters through the superior vena cava and points apically.  A view of the tricuspid valve from high within the RA.

To view the tricuspid valve in the RA, the camera enters through the superior vena cava and points apically.  A rather round example of the tricuspid valve.  The leaflet on the right (anterior) spans the length of the valve.  Off of the septal leaflet (on the left edge of the valve), the coronary sinus can be seen, with the space between these structures being the triangle of Koch.
View of the tricuspid valve from high in the RA, seen to the left of the septal leaflet (left portion of the valve) is the coronary sinus, partially obstructed by a Thebesian valve.

To view the tricuspid valve in the RA, the camera enters through the superior vena cava and points apically.  This tricuspid valve appears to have four leaflets.  Off of the septal leaflet (left portion of the valve) the coronary sinus can be seen.

To view the tricuspid valve in the RA, the camera enters through the superior vena cava and points apically.  Tricuspid valve seen with a large septal leaflet (on left) and leaflets about 2/3s and 1/3 the size opposite it.  To the left of the septal leaflet is the coronary sinus.

To view the tricuspid valve in the RA, the camera enters through the superior vena cava and points apically.  Tricuspid valve seen here, bordered by the RA free wall on the anterior portion of the valve.

The trabeculations in the right ventricular apex can be seen here. The muscular trabeculae can be seen contracting in synchrony.  The white connective tissues are conduction bands and allow the stimulation signal to travel from one portion of the heart to another.
View of the right ventricular apex.  The posterior papillary muscle is to the left, the septal wall to the top and center, and the anterior papillary muscle off screen to the lower right.
View of the right ventricular apex.  A high degree of trabeculation can be seen.  The small white bands are presumably conduction fibers.

The right ventricular apex is shown.  The base of the posterior papillary muscle is on the tops of the screen, and the base of the anterior papillary muscle is on the lower right corner of the screen.

In this view, the camera is placed through under the tricuspid valve, peering into the RV apex.  The white bands are chordae tendinae, which prevent the valve leaflets they are attached to above (tricuspid valve) from prolasping.  From below, the chordae tendinae are attached to papillary muscles, which can be seen in this image and look like little bumps.
Camera is looking into the right ventricular apex with the septal wall on the left and top and the free wall on the right and bottom
The extent of trabeculation (muscular tissue) as well as the different morphologies of the conduction bands (white strings) can be seen in this video from the right ventricular apex.

The RV apex is seen here as you look across the base of the apex. The moderator band can be seen clearly in the middle of the image spanning from one wall to the other. Also fatty deposits can be seen lining the trabeculae in various areas.

This video shows a close-up of a conduction band in the foreground with the trabeculations of the RV apex in the background. Also in the background you can see small connections from the cardiac conduction bands spanning from muscle to muscle.
The RV apex is seen here with various sizes of trabeculae. The thin white lines are conduction bands and the variety of ways they can be connected can be seen in this video.
The apex of the RV can be seen here. Large movements from the ventricular walls can be seen here. The amount of trabeculation in this specimen is less than others that can be seen on this site.

A view of the apex from deep within the trabeculae. The camera begins with a close-up of some trabeculae and conduction bands then pans backwards to see more of the ventricular walls and papillary muscles.
A view of the right ventricular apex showing a significant number of trabeculations and conduction bands.

View of the right ventricular apex with conduction bands (thin white string-like structures) and trabeculations.  The base of the posterior papillary muscle can be seen to the top right of the screen.

View of trabeculations and conduction bands throughout RV. Unique conduction band from the tricuspid valve to the anterior right ventricular wall. The tricuspid valve is to the upper right of the screen.
In this video the right ventricular apex is shown with trabeculae and connection bands situated against the walls of the ventricle. The camera then pans out to show more of the right ventricle.
The elaborate and intricate layout of the trabeculations and connection bands is visible here along with the shortening of the trabeculae and tissue during contractions.

The camera is viewing the walls of the right ventricle as well as the right ventricular apex. Two conduction bands can be distinguished in this video, one at the top left of the image and one just inside of the left side of the image.
View of the right ventricular apex.  This image displays the significant number of trabeculations and conduction bands in the apex of the right ventricle.
The right ventricular apex is seen with the anterior papillary muscle at the top of the screen initially.The shot zooms in on three different sections of the apex and shows the trabeculations.

In this image, the camera is sticking through the tricuspid valve and very near to the apex of the heart.  This apex is heavily trabeculated (dainty weblike structures) and thicker conduction bands can be seen connecting one side of the RV to the other, facilitating the fast conduction of electrical pulses throughout the chamber.
Perfusion fixed heart.  Camera advances towards right ventricular apex and into trabeculations.
Perfusion fixed heart.  Camera advances towards right ventricular apex and into trabeculations.
Another view of the apex of the RV.  The trabeculations seem to form along the wall of the RV, leaving the center open.
Peering toward the apex, with trabeculations seen along the wall of the ventricle and a large conduction band spanning the upper right corner of the image.

In this view, the camera is placed just through the tricuspid valve, peering into the RV apex.  Trabeculations seen in the apex of the right ventricle.  Larger, thicker conduction bands can be seen in the foreground of the picture.
Cardiac Trabeculae is seen in this image with their tortuous alignment. From the trabeculae cardiac conduction bands, white lines, can be seen connecting throughout the apex.

In this view, the camera is placed just through the tricuspid valve, peering into the RV apex.  Large conduction band spanning the RV apex in the upper right corner of the image.  In the lower left corner of the image a tricuspid leaflet can be seen reaching into the ventricle.
In this view, the camera is placed just through the tricuspid valve, peering into the RV apex.  View of a highly trabeculated apex, note the thicker conduction bands reaching across the ventricle.
A close-up view of the trabeculation within the RV apex. The yellow markings that are seen on the wall and trabeculae are fatty deposits that can be seen as the yellow spots on the muscular tissue.
In this view, the camera is placed just through the tricuspid valve, peering into the RV apex.  Trabeculations begin sparsely in the foreground and become much more dense within the deep apex.
Camera is deep within the apex of the heart.  In the lower left corner of the image is the heart wall and trabeculations can be seen growing off of the wall and across the apex of the RV.
Camera is deep within the apex of the heart.  Trabeculations seen in this image are much thicker than those viewed in previous hearts-- less occurance of the fine, weblike structure.
A view of a transected unfixed heart in which one can see the right ventricle, the ventricular septum, the anterior papillary muscle and a portion of the moderator band.

The tricuspid valve is seen here with the large anterior leaflet on the right side, the septal leaflet on the left side and the posterior leaflet is not seen here. Both of the visible leaflets are attached to the septal wall via chordae tendineae.

The right ventricular outflow tract is seen here with the septal wall on the right side and the free wall on the left. The tricuspid valve can be seen with the chordae tendineae attaching to the papillary muscles.

View of the right ventricular inflow tract.  The tricuspid valve is at the top left of the image connected to all three right ventricular papillary muscles via the chordae tendinae.  The anterior papillary muscle can be seen to the left of the image, the septal papillary muscle can be seen on the left connected to the septal wall and the posterior papillary muscle can be seen in the background.

The right ventricle is shown with the septal wall on the right, anterior papillary muscle in the middle of the screen, posterior papillary muscle in the back, and tricuspid valve off the top of the screen. A muscular moderator band can been easily observed connecting the anterior papillary muscle to the septal wall.
Perfusion fixed heart.  View of tricuspid valve from below, showing septal wall and location of His bundle approach from the right ventricle.

Image taken from within the RVA, looking laterally.  Here, the anterior-lateral wall can be seen, which is part of the right ventricular inflow tract.  Notice the trabeculations along the wall, as well as the papillary muscles in the foreground.

This image is taken from within the RVA, peering upward towards the tricuspid valve, which can be seen in the upper left corner of the image.  The chordae tendinae can be seen reaching off of the tricuspid leaflets and attaching to the septal wall papillaries.  Notice how the septal wall of the right ventricular inflow tract is very smooth in comparison with the lateral-anterior wall.

Looking through the tricuspid valve toward the posterior wall of the RVIT.  Note the level of trabeculations on the posterior wall vs. the smooth surface of the septal wall seen on the right hand side of the image.  Reaching up through the middle of the image is a septal papillary muscle.
The anterior wall is seen behind the anterior papillary muscles. Above the papillary muscles the anterior leaflet of the tricuspid valve can be seen.

In the left half of this image is a leaflet from the tricuspid valve.  The chordae tendinae are seen attaching to the septal papillary muscles.  Note the smooth surface of the septal wall.  The His bundle is just beneath the leaflet on the border of the septal wall and the right atrium.

View of papillary muscles and trabeculations on the septal wall, near the apex of the inflow tract.  The thin, white structures are the bottoms of the chordae tendinae attaching to the papillary muscles.

In this view, the camera is sitting in the ventricle, looking up toward the tricuspid valve (top of the screen) and the pulmonary valve (right edge of the screen).  The inflow tract of the ventricle is in the foreground of the image.

Trabeculations seen when peering toward the apex along the lateral wall of the ventricle.  The papillary muscles are in view, with the chordae tendinae reaching off of them and attaching to the tricuspid valve leaflets.

View from within the right ventricle, peering toward the septal wall.  In the upper portion of the image, a tricuspid leaflet can be seen, along with the chordae tendinae reaching down to attach to the papillary muscles below.
In this view, the leaflet form the tricuspid valve is completely open and is pressed against the septal wall.  The His bundle is within the high septal wall, just inferior to the atrial chamber.

Camera is in the right ventricle, looking toward the septal wall.  Near the top of the image, one of the tricuspid valve leaflets can be seen with the chordae tendinae reaching down to attach to the septal papillary muscles, which are not very prominent in this specimen.

In this movie, the camera begins in the high right ventricle, where the smooth wall of the septum can be seen.  It slowly moves through the tricuspid valve, where the white structure in the foreground is the septal leaflet.  Once through the valve, the floor of the atrium can be seen.

In this image, the camera is deep within the right ventricle, peering upward toward the tricuspid valve.  On the right side of the image is the septal wall/inflow tract-- note the rather smooth surface. To the left of this image, the right ventricular chamber opens up. The His bundle is positioned high and deep in the septal wall, just under the floor of the right atrium.

The septal wall of the right ventricle is seen here. The trabeculae can be seen throughout the tissue. The septal papillary can be located by following the chordae tendineae coming from the tricuspid down and connecting to the musculature.

In this shot, the camera is right at the level of the tricuspid annulus.  Here, another view of the septal leaflet of the tricuspid valve is seen, underneath which, deep within the septal wall, is the His bundle.  Note the many branches of chordae tendinae attaching to the septal wall.

This image is taken from the middle of the RV chamber, looking at the anterior-lateral surface.  In the foreground of the image, a papillary muscle is seen, with chordae tendinae reaching upward toward the leaflets of the tricuspid valve.
The tricuspid valve is just above the upper left hand corner of this image.  The smooth septal wall is seen straight ahead.

This image is take from deep within the right ventricle, looking upward toward the tricuspid valve from below.  Just outside of the upper left corner of the image is the right ventricular outflow tract, meaning that the inflow tract travels along the lower right corner of the image.

Great view of the septal wall/inflow tract.  This image is captured from just beneath the tricuspid annulus.  The septal leaflet can be seen in the upper left corner of the image and the anterior leaflet can barely been seen in the upper right corner of the image.

Here, the inflow tract of the RV is seen, along the septal wall.  Also, in front of the septal wall are the chordae tendinae attaching to the septal leaflet of the tricuspid valve at the top and the septal papillary muscle at the bottom.  A bit of loose tissue is seen caught on one of the chordae.

Peering through a chordae tendinae on the septal wall, the anterior/lateral wall of the RV can be seen-- much more trabeculated than the smooth septal wall.  The pulmonary valve can be seen from below in the upper left corner of the image.

In this view of the septal wall of the right ventricular inflow tract, the anterior papillary (bottom right) septal papillary (top right) and the posterior papillary muscle (middle left) can be seen in this image. View of the moderator band originating on the septal wall (right) and terminating at the base of the anterior papillary muscle (center).

The vertical structure in the background is a papillary muscle, near the top of which attaches to chordae tendinae. In this image the moderator band can be seen stretching from the interventricular septum (right side) to the anterior papillary muscle (left side). This is a good illustration of the complexities that can be found in such specimens. The Anterior papillary muscle seems to originate from both the moderator band as well as the anterior wall of the right ventricle.
Seen in the upper left corner of this image is a leaflet of the tricuspid valve.  Reaching across the width of the ventricle, beginning at the lower right corner of the image, is the moderator band.

In the upper left corner of this image is the tricuspid valve, as seen from below, in the open position.  The thick vertical band near the right edge of the image is the moderator band.  In its anatomically correct positioning, the moderator band is horizontal and spans across the right ventricle.

This image is captured from deep within the right ventricle, looking up toward the tricuspid valve, as is seen at the top edge of the image.  The moderator band is the structure that is reaching horizontally across the ventricle.  From the moderator band, a papillary muscle can be seen growing upward and attaching to one of the tricuspid leaflets.
Here, the moderator band can be seen attaching to one wall of the right ventricle, spanning the width of the ventricle and attaching to the opposing wall.
A very thick moderator band can be seen spanning the width of the right ventricle, off which, a papillary muscle grows vertically (see on the left edge of the image).
APM in middle, PPM behind it, moderator band at bottom of APM, septal wall top and right, free wall lower left
View of the anterior papillary muscle in the right ventricle.  The chordae tendinae can be seen arising from the top of the muscle.

View of the posterior papillary muscles of the right ventricle.  The tricuspid valve is to the top of the screen.  The anterior papillary muscle is seen on the left of the screen.  The moderator band can be seen at the very end of the clip towards the bottom right.

View of the right ventricular inflow tract.  The tricuspid valve is to the upper left off the screen, the septal wall and papillary muscles are in the middle of the screen and the upper right, and the anterior papillary muscle to the lower left.

View of the right ventricular inflow tract.  The tricuspid valve is to the upper right, the anterior papillary muscle to the bottom/bottom right, the septal papillary muscles to the upper right, and the posterior papillary muscle behind the anterior papillary muscle.

View of the right ventricular inflow tract.   The septal wall is to the right of the image, the anterior papillary muscle in the center, and the posterior papillary muscles in the background. Also visible is the moderator band in the lower central portion of the image, connecting the septal wall to the base of the anterior papillary muscle.

View of the right ventricular inflow tract.  The anterior papillary muscle can be seen in the foreground of the lower right corner and the posterior papillary muscle in the background with two distinct heads.  The free wall of the right ventricle is located on the left and center of the image.

The septal papillary muscle and tricuspid valve are located to the left and the pulmonic valve is located to the upper right off the screen.  The trabeculations that are visible in the bottom right of the image are located in the border between the septal wall and free wall.
View of the apex of the right ventricle.  A small conduction fiber can be seen in the foreground of the image, along with a high degree of trabeculation.

View of the anterior papillary muscle of the right ventricle.  Chordae tendinae can be seen connecting the head of the muscle to the tricuspid valve. View of the anterior papillary muscles of the right ventricle.  The tricuspid valve is off the screen to the top.  Chordae tendinae connecting the papillary muscle to the valve can be seen.  The free wall is to the left.

View of the septal wall of the right ventricular inflow tract.  Many small septal papillary muscles can be seen.  Chordae tendinae can be seen arising from the heads of these muscles as well as from the septal wall itself.  The anterior papillary muscle can be seen to the lower right of the image.
In this movie, a very small papillary muscle can be seen on the septal wall of the right ventricle.  The papillary muscle can be identified by the chordae tendinae attached to the top of it.
Here, the camera is positioned within the annulus of the tricuspid valve, peering downward upon the anterior papillary muscle (left edge of the image), which is attached to the tricuspid leaflet.

In this movie, multiple papillary muscles can be seen with multiple chodae tendinae reaching off the top of them.  The papillary against the wall near the center of the picture is a posterior papillary muscle.

Here a low profile papillary muscle can be seen against the septal wall of the right ventricle.  The white fixture near the top of the papillary muscle is the chordae tendinae.  The very thin bands seen in this movie are conduction bands, which help to carry the electrical impulses throughout the myocardium.

The chordae tendinae can be seen connecting to the heads of the anterior papillary muscle complex. The heart is in ventricular fibrillation, as evidenced by the fact that there is no co-ordinated contraction of the myocardium.

The posterior muscle complex of the right ventricle.  Due to the fact that the heart is in ventricular fibrillation there is no movement of fluid through the chamber and hence the tricuspid valve is not functioning.  As the valve is not closing the chordae attached to the papillary complex lie slack and are not functioning as they should.

The septal papillary muscle complex of the right ventricle can be seen in the center of the footage with the tricuspid valve to th3e right. Due to the heart being in ventricular fibrillation the subvalvular apparatus is not functioning correctly.
Close-up of papillary muscle; note the conduction bands connecting the ventricular walls to the papillary muscles.
A view of the posterior papillary muscle; in this movie, the camera pans towards the tricuspid valve near the end of the clip.  The heart is beating irregularly.

A good view of the posterior papillary muscle in RV (on the left, with the cordae above).  One can also observe conduction bands and the septal papillary muscle in the upper middle of this view; the base of the anterior papillary muscle is in the foreground to the right.

A view through the RVOT with the septal papillary muscles to the left; chordae tendinae are coming out of the bottom of the muscle.  A bifurcated anterior papillary muscle can be seen contracting in the foreground to the lower right.  The pulmonary valve can be observed closing in the background.

A close-up view of the base of the septal and anterior papillary muscles; the anterior one which is bifurcated is in the middle of the screen and the pulmonary valve can be observed in the background in the upper right.

The anterior (to the right) and posterior (to the left) muscle complexes of the right ventricle showing the connection bands and trabeculation at the base of the muscles and the multiple chordae tendinae reaching up to the tricuspid valve (above the image) from the muscle heads.
A view from the level of  the tricuspid valve looking down on posterior papillary muscle and into RV apex.

The septal papillary muscle complex in this heart shows three distinct papillary heads that connect to the tricuspid valve leaflets via the chordae tendinae.  The chordae from the main muscle head is fenestrated, an anatomical feature that can inhibit the placement of devices in the right ventricular apex.

A view of the papillary muscles from the annulus of the tricuspid valve.  The septal papillary muscle is to the left and is shown surrounded by trabeculations in the RV apex. The posterior papillary muscle can be seen to the lower right and the anterior one is to the middle right.
Papillary muscle; tricuspid valve is to the top of the screen.  Note the high degree of trabeculation.

The anterior papillary muscle complex of the right ventricle can be seen toward the rear of this clip with the posterior muscle in the foreground of the image.  Notice the bifurcation of the anterior muscle complex with the extensive trabeculations around the base and the network of conduction bands between the two muscle heads of the bifurcation.
A view of the posterior papillary muscle; trabeculations in RV apex can be seen in the background, the free wall is to the right.

The camera is positioned in the right ventricular outflow tract and provides a view of the anterior papillary muscle. The motion of the tricuspid valve can be observed in the movement of the chordae tendinae.

The camera is just below the tricuspid valve in the right ventricle. The anterior papillary muscle is slightly to the right of the screen. The thin white string-like structures are chordae tendinae that connect the papillary muscles to the valve leaflets to prevent the leaflets from prolapsing.
The posterior papillary muscle in the right ventricle is in the center of the screen. The moderator band can be seen in the background, connecting the septal wall (left) with the free wall (right).
View of the septal papillary muscle from its base (towards the left of the screen). At the top of the papillary muscle, the chordae tendinae can be seen; the pulmonary valve can also be seen.

Footage of the anterior papillary muscle complex showing a unique anatomical configuration whereby two muscles, with separate connections to the ventricle wall, join near the muscle heads and display conduction bands reaching across to the posterior complex.  The intricate trabeculation of the endocardial surface of the right ventricle can be seen at the base of the image.

The posterior muscle complex of this heart displays a maze of muscular and tendinous connections between he individual muscle heads.  The footage starts at the base of the complex and moves to the heads where the chordae tendinae attach to the leaflets of the tricuspid valve.

The septal papillary complex (to the left of the image) of the right ventricle shows many fenestrated chordae tendinae branching from small papillary heads to the tricuspid valve.  The smooth septal wall of the right ventricle can be seen in the background of the footage.
View of anterior papillary muscle with moderator band, seen on the left side, connecting papillary to septal wall.

The posterior papillary muscle complex with two unique muscle heads can be seen in this footage with chordae tendinae connecting the papillary heads to the tricuspid valve. This video clearly shows how the muscles tether the leaflets of the tricuspid maintain good leaflet coaptation and stop regurgitation.
The anterior papillary muscle complex can be seen  in this footage with a bifurcated muscle to the left of the image and a series of conduction bands branching off the base of the complex.
View fo the posterior papillary muscle in the right ventricle with a nice view of the chordae tendonae.

The posterior muscle complex can be seen in this footage that shows a series of muscle heads stemming form the ventricular wall and connecting to the valve via chordae tendinae.  This footage exemplifies the movement of the muscle during ventricular contraction and how each muscle is key to tethering the leaflets of the tricuspid valve to avoid regurgitation into the atrium.

View of the anterior papillary muscle of the right ventricle. Chordae tendinae can be seen connecting the head of the muscle to the tricuspid valve. A septal papillary muscle can also be seen on the left side of the screen.

View of the septal papillary muscle of the right ventricle connected to the septal wall to the right of the image. The tricuspid valve is at the top left of the image connected to all three right ventricular papillary muscles via the chordate tendinae.  The anterior papillary muscle can be seen to the left of the image and the posterior papillary muscle can be seen in the background.
A close up shot of the anterior papillary complex.  This footage shows a singular muscle head with multiple chordal connections to the valve above.
A close up of the base of the anterior papillary muscle complex showing the moderator band and a chordae tendinae branching off half way up the papillary muscle.

Perfusion fixed heart.  Camera shows the anterior papillary muscle and attachment to right ventricular endocardium before panning up to show the chordae tendinae and attachment to the tricuspid valve.

Perfusion fixed heart.  View of septal wall below tricuspid valve.  Two smaller papillary muscles are shown before the camera pans to a third larger papillary muscle.

In the foreground of this image the anterior papillary muscle can be seen, while in the background, a double headed posterior papillary muscle is seen.
Two papillary muscles are seen sprouting from the septal wall of this heart.  This image provides a great view of how detailed and ornate the chordae tendinae are.
Here, a large papillary muscle is seen near the anterior wall of the right ventricle with multiple chodae tendinae reaching off the top toward the tricuspid leaflets.
This image is taken when the camera is just beneath the tricuspid valve, looking down into the right ventricle.  The posterior papillary muscle can be seen in this view.

Here, a papillary muscle can be seen from below on the septal wall of the right ventricle.  Looking upward from the apex of the ventricle, the pulmonary valve can be seen in the lower portion of the image.

In this image, taken from within the right ventricle, multiple papillary muscles can be seen. On the left is the anterior/lateral wall of the ventricle, on which 2 papillary muscles can be seen.  Between these two wall, in the background of the image, can be seen another, posterior papillary muscle.

Multiple septal papillary muscles are seen in this image.  They are very low profile compared to the anterior and posterior papillaries, which generally grow out of the apex of the ventricle, instead of out of the ventricular wall, as the septal papillaries do.
