In this image, the septal papillary muscles are difficult to see, as they are so insignificant.  The easiest way to spot them is to trace the chordae tendinae back toward the septal wall, where they attach to the papillary muscles.

This image is captured from deep within the right ventricle, at an angle.  In this image, near the right edge, the tricuspid valve can be seen from below.  A relatively large septal papillary muscle can be seen reaching off of the septal wall, in the upper right portion of the image.

A close up shot of the anterior papillary muscle with the chordal attachment to the tricuspid valve in the upper right of the image.  The image is taken looking toward the apex of the heart and the posterior muscle complex can be seen behind.
When looking downward from just within the tricupsid valve, a large septal papillary muscle is seen.  Nothe the multiple head off of which many chordae tendinae attach.

The aortic (anterior) leaflet is to the bottom right of the screen.  A large LV band can be seen on the left of the screen traveling to the lower right.  This band attaches to the base of the APM, which is not visible in the clip.

The mitral valve can be seen as viewed from the left ventricular apex. The posterior papillary muscle is to the right of the screen. Chordae tendinae connect the valve’s leaflets to the papillary muscles to prevent the leaflets from prolapsing.
Mitral valve from left ventricular apex in working mode.
View of mitral valve in working mode from left ventricle; aortic valve on the left.
View of the mitral valve in working mode from below; the aortic valve is seen on the left.
View of the mitral valve in Langendorff mode from below; the aortic valve is on the left and the chordae tendonae are visible.
View of the mitral valve from the left ventricle.  The chordae tendinae of the valve can be clearly seen with the anterior papillary muscle to the right of the image.

The bottom of the mitral valve as seen from the left ventrical. The aortic valve is seen to the left of the mitral valve. A free floating growth is also seen bouncing around in the cordae tendinae of the mitral valve.

Footage of the functioning mitral valve viewed from the left ventricle.  The anterior leaflet can be seen to the top of the image and the posterior below.  The complex connections of the leaflets to the papillary muscles via the chordae tendonae of the left ventricle can also be seen.
The mitral valve as seen from the left ventricle.  The chordae tendineae can be seen connecting the valve leaflets to the papillary muscles on the ventricular wall.

This clip shows the mitral valve from below. This heart does not have stereotypical anatomy when it comes to the papillary muscles. There are at least three papillary muscles in this left ventricle, one can be seen at the top of the video (anterior papillary) and it may be attached to the other papillary muscle as a complex, bi or tri-fricated papillary complex. The posterior papillary muscle is also a part of a complex that is not seen as well with this video.

Perfusion fixed heart.  View of mitral valve from left ventricle.  Camera pans from showing the heads of the anterior and posterior papillary muscles to the chordae tendinae and their attachment to the aortic leaflet of the mitral valve.
View of one of the leaflets of the mitral valve from the LV, as well as the chordae tendinae attaching it to the papillary muscles.
A view of both leaflets of the mitral valve and chordae tendinae.
Upclose view of one of the leaflets of the mitral valve.
Looking upward at the mitral valve from below.  The chordae tendinae can be seen attaching the leaflets to the papillary muscles.
Good view of chordae tendinae attached to mitral valve leaflets from within the LV.

Perfusion fixed heart.  View of the mitral valve from the left ventricle.  The camera pans from a view including the posterior papillary muscle to one showing the anterior papillary muscle.  At the start of the clip, the septal wall can be seen on the left hand side of the image.  At the end of the clip, trabeculations can be seen on the free wall of the left ventricle.
Image of the mitral valve from below.  Near the bottom of the image on both the left and right sides, a papillary muscle can be seen.
Chordae tendinae seen reaching upward and attaching to the leaflets fo the mitral valve (thin white material).
View of the anterior papillary muscle in the left ventricle.  Chordae tendinae can be seen on the head of the muscle.

View of the anterior papillary muscle in the left ventricle.  Chordae tendinae can be seen on the head of the muscle.  The camera pans to include the posterior wall and part of the posterior papillary muscle towards the end of the clip.
View of the posterior papillary muscle of the left ventricle.  The septal wall is to the left, off the screen.  Chordae tendinae can be seen arising from the two heads of the muscle.

The base of the posterior (center) and the anterior (right) papillary muscles can be seen in this movie sequence. Of particular interest are the trabeculation and conduction bands near the apex where the papillary muscles join the ventricular free wall highlighting the complex anatomy of the left ventricular apex.

View of the anterior papillary muscle in the left ventricle.  The head of the posterior papillary muscle is directly below the camera off the bottom of the screen.  Chordae tendinae can be seen arising from both papillary muscles and heading off the top of the screen.

View of the posterior papillary muscle of the left ventricle.  There are two heads which are connected by a short fibrous band.  Chordae tendinae can be seen arising from both heads and heading towards the mitral valve, which is off the screen to the top.

View of the anterior papillary muscle in the left ventricle.  The head of the posterior papillary muscle is to the lower left of the screen.  Chordae tendinae can be seen arising from both muscles and heading off the top of the screen, towards the mitral valve.  Trabeculations on the free wall of the left ventricle can also be seen surrounding the anterior papillary muscle.

View of the papillary muscles in the left ventricle.  A bifurcated posterior papillary muscle can be seen on the right of the image.  The base of the anterior papillary muscle can be seen on the upper left of the image.

View of the posterior papillary muscles (there are 2) of the Left ventricle.  The camera initially shows the head of the muscles along with the associated chordae tendinae, and then pans to the body and base of the muscles.
View of the posterior papillary muscle of the LV, through the mitral valve.  The aortic (anterior) leaflet of the mitral valve is to the right and the mural (posterior) is to the left.
The posterior papillary muscle complex in this heart has a bifurcated head with chordae attaching to both anterior and posterior leaflets of the mitral valve.
Close-up view of the head of the PPM of the LV.

View of the three papillary muscles in the LV of this heart.  The APM is located to the left and the PPM to the far right of this clip, with the third papillary muscle in the center.  The APM and PPM are both connected to the third papillary muscle via an thin band resembling the chordae tendinae.
View of the chordae tendinae of the APM.  An accessory third papillary muscle can be seen in the background of this clip.
View of the anterior papillary muscle. Chordae tendinae can be seen at the head of the muscle. The papillary muscle is surrounded by trabeculations.

View of the posterior papillary muscle in the upper middle of the screen. The anterior papillary muscle can be seen to the right of the screen and the left ventricular apex is to the lower left of the screen.

View of the posterior papillary complex showing how the trabeculation of the left ventricular free wall often integrates with the papillary complex.

This movie shows the heads of the papillary muscles of the anterior complex seen looking from the left atrium through the atrioventricular valve.  The chordal attachments to each side of the camera connect to both leaflets of the mitral valve.

The movie shows two distinct papillary heads of the posterior muscle complex seen looking from the left atrium through the atrioventricular valve. Note the anomalous anatomy of the papillary head to the lower right of the movie, in particular the muscular connection to the left ventricular free wall from the papillary head as well as chordal attachments to the valve.
View of the anterior papillary muscle in the left ventricle; the posterior papillary muscle is visible near the end of the video clip.

View of the posterior papillary muscle in the left ventricle.  The chordae tendinae of the mitral valve can be seen to the left of the image and the apex of the left ventricle to the right.  A Millar® pressure catheter used to take left ventricular pressures can be seen in the image.
Anterior papillary muscle complex of the left ventricle.  The chordae tendonae connecting the papillary muscle to the mitral valve can be seen to the right of the image.
View of the posterior papillary muscle and the lateral wall of the left ventricle.  The chordae tendonae can be seen to the upper left of the video footage.

Posterior papillary muscle complex of the left ventricle.  Trabeculations and conduction bands of the left ventricular wall can be seen at the base of the papillary muscle to the left of the image.  The chordae tendonae connecting the muscle complex to the mitral valve can be seen to the right.
The anterior papillary muscle complex of the left ventricle shows two large papillary heads with multiple chordal attachments to the leaflets of the mitral valve.

The complexity of chordae attachment the mitral valve to the papillary muscles is shown with the view within the left ventricle. In this anatomy, three papillary muscles are present in the left ventricle have the majority of the chordae connections however other connections can be seen attaching other points including the left ventricular free wall.
Perfusion fixed heart.  Camera advances through mitral valve into left ventricle.  Shows anterior papillary muscle and trabeculation on left ventricular free wall.

The very end of the clip shows the base of the posterior papillary muscle, where a bifurcation of the muscle can be seen.
Seen here is a large, fused posterior papillary muscle located in the LV.  Chordae tendinae can be seen reaching upward and attaching to the mitral valve leaflets.

The anterior papillary complex shows a trifurcated complex with three distinct tips to the muscle structure.  The chordae tendinae from this complex attach to both the anterior and posterior leaflets of the mitral valve above highlighting the complexity of these anatomical structures.

The posterior papillary complex in this heart exhibits two distinct muscles each with multiple heads (where groups of chordae attach). Note the tendinous band between the two muscle that also exhibits a chordal attachment to the valve above.
Large anterior papillary muscle with two heads found in the LV.  In the upper left corner of this image, a mitral valve leaflet can be seen, with chordae tendinae spanning between the two structures.
Anterior papillary muscles in the LV seen from above, near the mitral valve annulus.
Posterior papillary muscle seen in the background of this image.  This muscle has a singular base and two heads.

A highly elaborate posterior papillary complex viewed from the left atrium through the mitral valve. This complex exhibits multiple muscle heads with chordal attachments to both leaflets and tendinous connections between the muscles.
Papillary muscles can be seen in the foreground and background of this image, both being rather broad and long.

Very broad posterior papillary muscle with multiple chordae tendinae extending off the head toward the mitral valve leaflets above.
A close-up view of the anterior papillary complex.  Chordae tendinae from the papillary head connect to both the anterior and posterior leaflets of the mitral valve.

In this image, taken from just below the mitral valve annulus, both the posterior and anterior papillary muscles can be seen.

View of the left ventricle interventricular septal wall.  A head of the posterior papillary is visible on the left of the screen.
Left ventricular septal wall with part of the anterior papillary muscle complex in the foreground.

The short axis slice at the valve level displays the orientation of the valves in relation to each other.  This specimen shows how the annuli of the mitral and aortic valves are linked and displays the way the cardiac skeleton can be identified using MR imaging.

This short axis image of the heart shows the close proximity of the mitral, tricuspid and aortic valves.  The leaflets of the pulmonary and tricuspid valves can be seen within their respective valve annuli.

This short axis slice of the specimen beautifully shows the annulus of the mitral valve. Additionally, the left circumflex artery can be seen curving around heart above the mitral annulus and the left anterior descending artery diving down into the myocardium adjacent to the pulmonary valve annulus.
This valvular level short axis slice depicts the leaflets of the aortic valve and displays the proximity of the aortic valve to the mitral.
Short axis slice of the heart at valve level. The axes are labeled as follows: S=superior, I=inferior, A=anterior, P=posterior, R=right, L=left
This MR slice shows the mitral and aortic valve annuli in the cardiac skeleton.  The three cusps of the aortic valve can also be seen in the center of the image.
The tri leaflet structure of the aortic valve can be seen in the center of this short axis slice of the heart at the valve level.  The annulus of the mitral valve is also clearly identifiable.
The pulmonary valve of this heart seems to be heavily dilated, possibly due to pulmonary hypertension.
The three cusps and the commissures of the aortic valve can be clearly seen in this short axis slice of the heart.
Short axis slice of the heart at valve level. The axes are labeled as follows: S=superior, I=inferior, A=anterior, P=posterior, R=right, L=left
The proximity of the aortic and mitral valves is displayed in this short axis MR image showing how each valve annulus makes up part of the cardiac skeleton.
The relationship between the mitral, aortic and tricuspid valve annulus can be seen in this short axis MR slice.
The short axis MR slice at the valve level clearly shows the orientation of the leaflets of the aortic valve and the proximity of the aortic valve to the mitral annulus.
Short axis slice of the heart at valve level. The axes are labeled as follows: S=superior, I=inferior, A=anterior, P=posterior, R=right, L=left
The short axis valve level slice displays the tricuspid nature of both semilunar valves.  The right atrial appendage can also be seen in to the right of the image.

This MR slice of the heart shows the position of the aortic valve in relation to the mitral valve. Additionally the positioning of the aortic leaflets can be made out with the right coronary artery branching off the aorta to the right of the sinus of valsalva.
The coronary sinus can clearly be seen wrapping around the annulus of the mitral valve in the posterior region of the left ventricle in this short axis slice.
The relative positions of the aortic and mitral valve annulus can be clearly seen in this short axis image.

The orientation of the leaflets of the aortic valve are shown in the center of this short axis MR slice.  One should also note the positioning of the mitral valve annulus in relation to the coronary sinus to the posterior portion of the heart and to the aortic valve in the center of the heart\.

The walls of the right atrium and the left atrial appendage (to the far left of the image) are clearly defined in this short axis slice. Additionally, the walls of the pulmonary artery and the aorta are clearly recognizable as an example of how vascular tissue is imaging differently to myocardial tissue.

The short axis slice clearly displays the interaction of the four valve through the cardiac skeleton with the aortic valve in the center, the pulmonary valve to the top, the mitral to the left and the edge of the tricuspid (below the right atrium (RA)).
This MR slice of the heart clearly shows the junction of the cardiac skeleton between the aortic, mitral and tricuspid valves.
In this short axis slice the right coronary artery can clearly be seen branching off the aorta from the right coronary cusp.

The leaflets of the tricuspid, mitral aortic valve can be seen in this short axis slice. Additionally, it is possible to make out some of the coronary vessels within the myocardial fat around the heart.

This short axis MR slice at the level of the cardiac valves beautifully shows that this heart has a bicuspid aortic valve.  This congenital defect is clearly indicated in the image by the way the two valve leaflets form a figure of eight shape in the aortic annulus.  Bicuspid aortic valves occur in approximately 1-2% of the population and are usually treated by surgically replacing the valve.

This short axis slice clearly depicts the three leaflets of the aortic valve.  The gap in the inter atrial septum was caused when the heart was excised due to a large portion of the inferior vena cava being removed with the liver to aid in attachment of that organ to a recipient.

This MR short axis slice is slightly higher in the heart than many of the others, just above the cardiac skeleton.  The coronary sinus can clearly be seen curving around the mitral valve annulus and ending at the ostium in the right atrium.
This short axis MR slice nicely shows the mitral valve annulus and the close proximity of the aortic, mitral and tricuspid valves.

The pulmonary artery can clearly be recognized in this short axis slice to the top of the image.  Additionally, part of the left atrial appendage can be seen just to the upper left of the mitral and aortic valves.

This short axis slice clearly shows the tri-leaflet nature of the pulmonary valve, to the top of the image.  Interestingly, due to the orientation of the heart in the scanner this short axis slice shows the aortic annulus to be almost the size of the mitral annulus.  Such an image exemplifies the importance of ensuring your scan in in the plane of the annulus when you are imaging to take measurements.
A short axis MR slice of the heart just above the cardiac skeleton.

This short axis slice of the heart nicely shows the tri-leaflet orientation of the aortic valve. Additionally, to the bottom of the image the coronary sinus can be seen sweeping around the mitral annulus and connecting to the right atrium at the ostium.
This MR slice shows the tricuspid, mitral and aortic valve annuli in the cardiac skeleton.  The dark spots are due to air in the coronary vessels affecting the MR scans.

The tri leaflet structure of the aortic valve can be clearly seen in this short axis slice.  The dark patches in the pectinate muscles of the right atrium are trapped pockets of air that affect the MR imaging process.
The proximity of the aortic and mitral valves is evidenced in this short axis MR image showing how each valve annulus makes up part of the cardiac skeleton.

This short axis slice of the heart shows the aortic valve in the center of the image with the two branches of the left coronary artery, the left anterior descending artery and the left circumflex artery.  Additionally, the leaflets of the pulmonary valve can be seen at the top of the image and the coronary sinus can be seen connecting to the right atrium at the base of the image.  Interestingly the thebesian valve, at the coronary sinus ostium, can also be seen on this MR slice due to the high resolution of the image.
This short axis slice art the level of the valves shows the close proximity of all four cardiac valves, (the tricuspid valve lies slightly inferior to this MR slice below the right atrium).

The left circumflex artery can be seen in this image curving from where it branches from the left coronary artery (to the upper left of the aortic valve) around the mitral valve annulus adjacent to the coronary sinus before diving down into the myocardium of the left ventricular free wall (below the mitral annulus).

Due to the fact that this short axis slice is not in the plane of the aortic valve annulus the valve is depicted as having an oval shape.  This is not the case and such images reinforce the need to be certain that you are imaging in the plane of the anatomical feature you are analyzing when taking anatomical measurements.

In this short axis slice the non coronary leaflet of the aortic valve can be seen in the plane of the slice (the grey colored leaflet toward the base of the image). Additionally, the coronary sinus ostium can be seen where the coronary sinus dumps the venous return from the myocardium back into the right atrium (at the base of the image).

This short axis slice of the specimen beautifully shows the annulus of the mitral valve. Additionally, the right coronary artery can be seen branching off from the right coronary cusp of the aortic valve (just above the tricuspid valve annulus).

The short axis slice at the valve level displays the orientation of the valves in relation to each other.  This specimen shows how the annuli of the mitral and aortic valves are linked and displays the way the cardiac skeleton can be identified using MR imaging.

The tri-leaflet structure of the aortic valve can be seen in the center of this short axis slice.  Additionally, the right coronary artery can be seen branching off the right coronary cusp of the aortic valve and the close interaction of the aortic and mitral valves can be seen.
The proximity of the aortic, mitral and tricuspid valves is displayed in this short axis MR image showing how each valve annulus makes up part of the cardiac skeleton.

This short axis slice of the heart nicely shows two of the coronary vessels: the right coronary artery branching off the aorta (to the right of the image) and the coronary sinus wrapping around the back of the mitral annulus (to the left of the image).
The tri leaflet structure of the aortic valve can be seen in the center of this short axis slice of the heart at the valve level.  The annulus of the mitral valve is also clearly identifiable.
This MR slice of the heart clearly shows the junction of the cardiac skeleton between the aortic, mitral and tricuspid valves.
The short axis slice of the heart can be used to compare the four annuli of the cardiac valves.  In this specimen we can also see the right coronary artery wrap around the back of the right atrium.

Part of the non coronary cusp of the aortic valve (in the center of the image) can be seen in this short axis slice of the heart.  This specimen also exhibits a significant amount of epicardial fat on the right side of the heart, to the right of the image.
This MR slice of the heart clearly shows the junction of the cardiac skeleton between the aortic, mitral and tricuspid valves.

The short axis image shown here exemplifies the mitral valve annulus and it's proximity to the aortic valve.  This particular specimen also exhibits a large coronary sinus ostium, seen to the left of the right atrium.

Additionally the papillary muscle complexes of the left ventricle can be clearly identified.  The dark area at the top of the interventricular septum within the epicardial fat is caused by an air pocket in the great cardiac vein.

Heart 53 was reanimated in the Visible Heart® apparatus and hence shows distinct edema (thickening due to the absorption of water) of the ventricular walls.
The effects of left ventricular hypertrophy can be seen in the short axis slice depicting the tick walled, low volume left ventricle.
Short axis view of the heart. The axes are labeled as follows: S=superior, I=inferior, A=anterior, P=posterior, R=right, L=left

The very thick walls of the left ventricle are typical of ventricular hypertrophy.  The small volume and thick walls limits the hearts ability to move blood whilst pumping.  This specimen also displays a large amount of epicardial fat on the free wall of the right ventricle.

This short axis slice of the heart shows some slight dilation of the ventricles emphasized by the large chamber size and relatively thin ventricular walls.  The image also exemplifies the differences between the papillary muscle complexes of the left and right ventricles.

This specimen shows severe hypertrophy of the left ventricle as evidenced by the thick ventricular walls and the small chamber volume.  This anatomical shape is usually the result of end stage cardiac disease possibly brought on by hypertension or other myocardial diseases.
The inferior and superior papillary muscles of the left ventricle can clearly be seen in this short axis slice that shows dilation of the ventricles.
Short axis view of the heart. The axes are labeled as follows: S=superior, I=inferior, A=anterior, P=posterior, R=right, L=left

The hypertrophy of the left ventricle and the dilation of the right ventricle can be seen in this short axis mid-ventricular slice.  Such thickening of the left side only is often due to overloading of the left side caused by hypertension or aortic stenosis.
The mid-ventricular MR slice of the heart displays the dilation of the left and right ventricles as well as the papillary muscles of the mitral valve.

This short axis MR slice displays the significant hypertrophy of the left ventricle resulting in a small ventricular volume and a large wall thickness.  By contrast the right ventricle displays thin walls and a large volume indicating some dilation of the chamber.
Short axis view of the heart. The axes are labeled as follows: S=superior, I=inferior, A=anterior, P=posterior, R=right, L=left

The short axis slice shows the difference between right and left ventricular papillary muscles.  Additionally, the effects of left ventricular hypertrophy can be seen evidencing the thick walls and low volume of the left ventricle.

The papillary muscles of the left and right ventricle can be seen in this short axis slice of the heart.  The change in tissue properties along the inferior portion of the left ventricle may be due to degradation of the myocardium either via an infarct or a myocardial infection.

The small volume of the right ventricle in relation to the left in this short axis slice is slightly misleading due to the fact that the slice cuts through the right ventricle close to the apex of the chamber.

The difference between the wall thickness of the left and right ventricle can clearly be identified in this short axis image.  Additionally, the difference in the size and positioning of the left and the right papillary muscles can be seen.

This short axis MR slice displays the slight hypertrophy of the left ventricle and shows the difference between the papillary muscle of each ventricle.  Additionally the trabeculations of the right ventricle can be seen.

The size and wall thickness of the ventricles of this heart could be considered "healthy"  However, although wall thickness and chamber volume is a good indication of cardiac health, it does not necessarily guarantee a good cardiac output.
The short axis slice through the ventricles clearly indicates the difference in wall thickness between the left and the right chambers.
The papillary muscles of the left and right ventricle can be seen in this short axis slice of the heart.

This short axis slice of the heart at the ventricular level displays the anatomical differences between the papillary muscles of the left and the right ventricles.  The right ventricular papillary muscles are generally smaller in cross-sectional area due to the lower forces required to tether the tricuspid valve.
Short axis slice of the right and left ventricle.  A large amount of epicardial fat can be seen on this specimen.
This short axis slice of the left and right ventricles shows slight enlargement of the left side.  This can be attributed to the extra work required to push blood through the bicuspid aortic valve.

The short axis slice through the ventricles shows  two areas of relatively thick epicardial fat.  These run along the anterior interventricular sulcus, to the top of the image, and down the free wall of the right ventricle, to the right of the image.  These fat layers are designed to protect the coronary vessels serving the ventricles.
The hypertrophy of the left ventricle can clearly be seen in this image in addition to significant amount of epicardial fat, particularly on the right side.

The heart shown here is from a patient diagnosed with hypertension and coronary artery disease.  These pathologies have led to the slight hypertrophy of the left ventricle and the dilation of the right, as evidenced in this short axis MR slice of the ventricles.

This heart is from a patient diagnosed with hypertension and diabetes.  Consequently the extra stress on the left side of the heart has led to hypertrophy of the left ventricle as evidenced by it's wall thickness when compared to the right.
The papillary muscles of the left and right ventricle can be seen in this short axis slice of the heart.

This specimen show the signs of some ventricular dilation possibly due to cardiomyopathy or congestive heart failure.  The papillary muscle of both the left and the right ventricle can be clearly seen in the image.
The short axis slice at the mid ventricular level shows the differences between the ventricular walls and the papillary muscles of the left and the right side of the heart.
The short axis mid ventricular slice of the heart shows the significant differences between the endocardial surfaces of the left and the right ventricles.

The ventricles of this heart show the distinct differences between the endocardial surfaces and papillary muscles of the left and right ventricles.  The change in gray scale between the myocardial tissue of the left and the right ventricle may be a result of the prolonged duration of asystole (causing the tissue to become ischemic) that this patient underwent before stabilizing.

The dilation of both the left and the right ventricle can be seen in this short axis slice of the heart.  This dilation results in a large chamber size that requires more muscular force to contract and therefore produce a meaningful cardiac output.

The difference between the wall thickness of the left and right ventricle can clearly be identified in this short axis image.  In this specimen the left side of the heart is showing some signs of ventricular hypertrophy as evidenced by the ratio of the chamber volume to the wall thickness.

The papillary muscles of the left ventricle are nicely defined in this short axis MR slice through the ventricles.  The image nicely demonstrates the varied anatomy of the endocardial surface of both left and right chambers.

The cross sectional view of the left and right ventricles, as displayed in this short axis MR slice, shows slight hypertrophy of the left ventricular free wall, potentially due to increased afterload on the left ventricle.

The circular cross-sectional shape of the left ventricle in this specimen indicates some slight dilation of the chamber.  This is confirmed when looking at the chamber volume to wall thickness ratio in both the short and long axis views.

The two papillary complexes of the left ventricle can be clearly identified in this short axis slice of the ventricles.  The image also depicts the difference in the wall thickness and ventricular volumes of the left and right side of the heart.

This heart is from a patient diagnosed with hypertension.  Although the systemic disease is usually associated with hypertrophy, in this patient it has chronically stressed the heart causing the ventricles to dilate as evidenced by the round cross-sectional shape of the left ventricle and the large cross-sectional area of the right.
This short axis ventricular slice shows the differences between the endocardial anatomy of the left and right ventricles with the two papillary complexes of the left ventricle clearly visible.

The ventricular short axis slice of this heart shows slight dilation of the chambers. The ventricular walls are relatively thick indicating that although dilated the heart may have been able to move a significant amount of blood around the body. However, this anatomical shape indicates the onset of congestive heart failure and over time the increasing volume of the chambers will effectively reduce the cardiac output.  This situation is exaggerated by the fact that the patient was listed as being hypertensive.

The epicardial fat layers in the anterior and posterior interventricular sulci can be seen in the short axis slice of the ventricles.  This fat layer is there to protect the cardiac vessels serving the lower regions of the ventricles.

This short axis slice of the ventricles shows the significant hypertrophy of the left ventricle and the dilation of the right.  It can be seen that the  wall thickness of the left side is comparable to the chamber diameter, this ratio results in a very strong ventricle moving a small volume of blood, usually against a large ventricular afterload.  The patient was diagnosed with chronic pulmonary obstruction and hypertension which over time have caused the dilation of the right ventricle and the hypertrophy of the left.

This short axis slice from a heart with no medically recorded cardiac pathologies shows some slight dilation to the chambers.  This is most probably due to the age of the patient and shows how a heart can exhibit some of the anatomical symptoms of the early stages of cardiac disease without effecting the global organ function. Interestingly, this heart shows a relatively large epicardial fat pad on the anterior surface of the heart (to the top of the image).

This specimen show the signs of some ventricular dilation possibly due to cardiomyopathy or congestive heart failure.  The intricate trabeculation of the left and right ventricles can be clearly seen in the image.
The papillary muscles of the left ventricle are clearly defined in this short axis MR slice through the ventricles.
The cross sectional view of the left and right ventricles, as displayed in this short axis MR slice, highlights the differences between the left and the right sides of the heart.
The differences in the papillary muscles of the left and right ventricles are clearly defined in this short axis MR slice.

Significant hypertrophy of the left ventricle can be seen in this short axis slice of the heart.  Such an increase in the ventricular wall thickness results in the enlargement of the papillary complexes and the stiffening of the ventricular walls.

Four-chamber view of the heart. The axes are labeled as follows: S=superior, I=inferior, A=anterior, P=posterior, R=right, L=left

The four chamber view of the heart displays the softball shape of this particular heart indicating the possibility of dilated cardiomyopathy.  The MR slice displays the distinct differences between the left and right sides of the heart.

Heart 53 was reanimated in the Visible Heart® apparatus and hence shows distinct edema (thickening due to the absorption of water) of the ventricular walls.

The four chamber scan for this specimen shows the hypertrophic left ventricle.  However, due to the atrial walls collapsing during the scanning process the anatomic features of the atria are not readily viewable.
Four-chamber view of the heart. The axes are labeled as follows: S=superior, I=inferior, A=anterior, P=posterior, R=right, L=left

The four chamber view of the current specimen displays the large volume of the atria in this specimen.  The heart displays the ventricular anatomy of a hypertrophic heart and consequently may have partially distended atrial anatomy, as evidenced by the MR image.  The slice shows the papillary muscles of both ventricles and the leaflets of the tricuspid and mitral valves.

The long axis view of this specimen shows all four chambers of the heart and beautifully exhibits the two atrioventricular valves, the mitral and the tricuspid.  The trabeculation of the endocardial surface of the right ventricle is also clearly visible as well as the papillary muscle complexes of both ventricles.

The left ventricular hypertrophy of this specimen is clearly viewed in this four chamber long axis slice. The volume to wall thickness ratio of the left side is significantly different to the right indicating the  left side has increased in size in order to push blood against the high blood pressure.

The four chamber view of this heart shows the dilation of the ventricles in this specimen.  The dilation of the chambers due to certain cardiac pathologies eventually results in the reduced cardiac output of the heart and can lead to cardiac death.
Four-chamber view of the heart. The axes are labeled as follows: S=superior, I=inferior, A=anterior, P=posterior, R=right, L=left

The MR image displays the significant hypertrophy of the left ventricle and the dilation of the right ventricle as evidenced by the wall thickness of both.  This pathology is usually the result of the left heart working hard against hypertension or a stenotic aortic valve.

The four chamber MR slice of this specimen show the distinct dilation of the chambers resulting a thin walls and a reduction in the cardiac output.  Of particular interest is the thickness of the right ventricle at the apex.
The four chamber view of the heart displays the hypertrophy of the left ventricle in relation to the right and shows the large amount of epicardial fat surrounding the heart.
Four-chamber view of the heart. The axes are labeled as follows: S=superior, I=inferior, A=anterior, P=posterior, R=right, L=left

This four chamber slice depicts the sinus of valsalva, the area of the aorta immediately after the aortic valve, and hence would clinically be considered a five chamber view.  The mitral valve can be clearly seen between the left atrium and ventricle.  The contrast between the muscle, fat and blood vessels of the myocardium can be seen in this high definition MR slice.

The four chamber of this specimen indicates an un-natural anatomy of the high interventricular septum.  The thinning of the septum as you move away from the apex is due to the repair of a ventricular septal defect.  The mitral and tricuspid valve leaflets and subvalvular apparatus can also be seen in the image.
The four chamber view shows the left and the right side of this heart simultaneously and allows cardiologists to compare the size and features of the two sides during diagnosis.
The left and the right chambers of the heart are clearly visible in this long axis image.
The leaflets and the sub valvular apparatus of the mitral and tricuspid valves can be clearly identified in this four chamber image.

The four chamber view of this specimen displays the left and right chambers of the heart. Size and proportions of this heart could be considered "healthy", although it must be noted that this does not always relate to good cardiac heath.

The four chamber long axis view shows the anatomy of the interventricular septum.  This image displays how thin the septum can be as it approaches the cardiac skeleton (at the very top of the left ventricular outflow tract, just below the aortic valve).  This area of the heart is known as the membranous septum and is of particular interest to researchers and clinicians working with the aortic valve.
The mitral and tricuspid valves can be clearly seen in this four chamber image.  The dark areas at the top of the atria are due to air pockets within the heart when the specimen wad scanned.

This long axis slice of the heart clearly show all four chambers and the two atrio-ventricular valves.  The dense trabeculation at the apex of the right ventricle of this heart may increase the difficulty of implanting a RV apex pacing lead.

The four chamber long axis view of this heart shows the right ventricular anterior papillary muscle and the chordae tendinae reaching up to the tricuspid valve. This particular specimen also displays a thin membranous septum, at the top of the interventricular septum.

The long axis four chamber slice of this heart exhibits the hypertrophy of the left side in relation to the right, caused by the work required to move blood through the bicuspid aortic valve.  This particular patient also suffered a myocardial infarction and received three coronary artery stents, both factors which can contribute to overall hypertrophy of the ventricles.

The four chamber long axis image of this heart clearly shows the differences between the left and the right ventricles with a beautiful image of a right ventricular papillary muscle.  Of particular interest in this image is the poor structural anatomy of the interventricular septum, this may have been caused by the myocardial infarction suffered by the patient.
The four chamber long axis slice shows the distinct hypertrophy of the left ventricle and the significant thickness of the epicardial fat layer around the right ventricle.

This four chamber MR slice clearly show the hypertrophy of the left ventricle and the dilation of the right ventricle and both atria. These symptoms are often the result of systemic hypertension, as this patient was diagnosed with.

The hypertrophy of the left ventricle and the dilation of the right side are clearly evidenced in this four chamber view.  Additionally the anatomical structure of the membranous septum can be seen just below the mitral valve at the top of the interventricular septum.

This long axis slice of the heart exemplifies the difference between the left and the right sides of the heart.  It also shows the trabeculation of the right ventricular apex and how the endocardial surface of the right ventricle is highly complex.

The four chamber long axis view clearly shows the dilation of the atria and of the two ventricles as evidenced by the chamber size in relation to the annular size of the mitral and tricuspid valves.  Chordae tendinae connecting the respective valves to the ventricular free walls can be seen on each side.
The left and the right chambers of the heart are clearly visible in this long axis image.
The four chamber view of this heart shows the significant dilation of the two atria as well as some possible scarring to the myocardium of the interventricular septum.

This four chamber slice shows the difference between the left and the right sides of the heart and beautifully exhibits the mitral and tricuspid valves that control blood flow between the atria and ventricles. The apparent damage to the right ventricular wall can be seen in this image as evidenced by the different coloration of the myocardial tissue on the right rather than the left.
The dilation of the left and right ventricles can be clearly seen in this four chamber long axis image.  Of particular note is the very thin interventricular septum and right ventricular apex.

This four chamber long axis view of the heart exemplifies the variability in the anatomy of the right ventricular apex and papillary muscle complexes caused by the distinct trabeculation in that area of the heart.

The four chamber view of this specimen displays the left and right chambers of the heart. Size and proportions of this heart could be considered "healthy", although it must be noted that the dimensions of the heart alone does not always relate to good cardiac function.
This long axis MR slice of the heart shows all four chambers and clearly indicates the hypertrophy of the left ventricular free wall, to the right of the image.
The four chamber view shows the left and the right side of this heart simultaneously and allows cardiologists to compare the size and features of the two sides during diagnosis.
The mitral valve, tricuspid valve and the left and the right chambers of the heart are clearly visible in this long axis image.
The four chamber view of this heart shows the significant dilation of the atria and ventricles as evidenced by the large chamber volumes and the relatively thin walls.

The four chamber view of the heart displays the anatomical differences between the left and the right sides of the organ with the two atrio-ventricular valves being clearly identified. This specimen displays significant dilation of the two atria as evidenced by their size relative to the ventricles.

As the scale in this four chamber slice suggests this is a large specimen.  The chambers of the heart are slightly dilated, this increases the chamber volume and therefore the filling time, assuming the annuli of the atrio-ventricular valves have remained constant.  In the long run this can significantly reduce cardiac output and be detrimental to the heart.

The leaflets and chordae tendinae of the two atrio-ventricular valves can be seen in this long axis four chamber slice. The heart also displays significant dilation to all four chambers due to clinically diagnosed hypertension.

The very thick walls and small volume of the left ventricle can be seen in this four chamber view of the heart.  In contrast the right ventricle and atrium show signs of dilation caused by chronic pulmonary obstruction.

This four chamber slice of the heart exhibits the dilation of the left atrium.  Additionally, the image beautifully shows one of the papillary heads of a complex in the left ventricle, note that the head of the papillary muscle has two distinctive tips that connect to both the anterior and posterior leaflets of the mitral valve.
The four chamber view of this heart shows evidence of ventricular dilation, thin ventricular wall and large chamber volumes.

Although not clinically diagnosed the anatomical structure of this large heart indicates the progression of a dilated cardiomyopathy.  This diagnosis is based upon the  ratio of the ventricular wall thickness and the chamber volumes.

The four chamber view of the heart shows the differences between the left and the right sides of the heart as well as the significant amounts of epicardial fat on the right side, to the right of the image.  Interestingly, the image also indicates that this heart has a atrial septal defect, a hole between the right and left atrium.
The left and the right chambers of the heart as well as the left ventricular outflow tract and the start of the aorta are clearly visible in this long axis image.

The hypertrophy of the left ventricle can be seen in this four chamber long axis view as evidenced by the thick walls of the free wall and the septum.  Slight dilation of the left atrium can also be seen in the image.

The long axis two chamber slice of the ventricle shows the clear difference between the wall thicknesses of the ventricle and atrium.  This heart also displays some trauma at the apex of the ventricle, this is due to the trans-apical insertion of a device post-mortem.

The long axis two chamber slice of the left ventricle clearly depicts the mitral valve between the atrium and ventricle.  The wall thickness of the ventricle indicates the possibility of LV hypertrophy and the large left atrium may be due to either mitral valve disease or hypertension.

The long axis slice of the left ventricle clearly shows the posterior (or inferior) papillary muscle, the mitral valve and the coronary sinus.  Interestingly, the apex of the left ventricle in this specimen is unusually thin.

The MR slice through the two chambers of the left side shows the left atrium and ventricle separated by the mitral valve.  Note the thinness of the ventricle wall at the apex and the slightly dilated shape.

The left side of the heart is imaged here in this long axis slice.  The left atrium can be seen to be slightly dilated, possibly due to increased systemic pressures as a result of the patients diagnosed hypertension.

This two chamber long axis slice of the left side shows the large chamber size of the left ventricle and beautifully shows how the papillary muscle complexes of the left side, in this case the posterior/inferior complex, can connect to both leaflets of the mitral valve.

A papillary muscle head of the posterior papillary muscle complex can be seen, to the left of the ventricle, connecting to the mitral valve leaflet through chordae tendinae.

This two chamber slice of the hearts left ventricle and atrium shows the dilation of the ventricle also shows evidence of dilation of the pulmonary artery.  This may be due to pulmonary hypertension causing distension of the vessel over the years.

The relationship of the coronary sinus and the mitral valve annulus can be seen in this two chamber long axis view of the heart.  The image also shows the posterior/inferior papillary muscle complex, to the left of the ventricle.

Due to the orientation of the heart in the scanner the wall of the left ventricle is made to look thicker in this two chamber long axis slice.  This is due to the fact that the plane of the slice is not aligned with the axis of the left ventricle and consequently the intersection of the myocardium is not perpendicular to the epicardial and endocardial surfaces.
The two chamber long axis slice of this heart beautifully show both papillary complexes of the left ventricle, the posterior/inferior complex and the anterior/superior complex.

Part of the posterior/inferior muscle complex can be seen to the right of the ventricle in this long axis view of the left side.  The image also shows how the coronary sinus position relative to the mitral valve annulus can change significantly.

This two chamber long axis slice of the heart shows the slight dilation of the left ventricle.  Chronic dilation of the chamber slowly reduces the cardiac output of the ventricle over time as the volume increases disproportionately to the thickness of the myocardium, weakening the ventricle walls.

The MR slice seen here shows significant dilation of the left atrium.  Part of the posterior/inferior papillary muscle complex connecting to both the anterior and posterior leaflets of the mitral valve can be seen to the left of the ventricle.
The large volume of the left ventricle is evidenced in this two chamber left sided MR slice.  Part of the left ventricular outflow tract can also be seen in the image.

The dilation of the left atrium and ventricle can be seen in the two chamber image here.  Other significant anatomical features seen in the image include the mitral valve chordae tendinae, the coronary sinus and the comparison of the vessel walls of the aorta and the pulmonary artery.  The dark spots in the image are due to air pockets within the specimen that affect the MR imaging.

The severe constriction of the left ventricle can be easily seen in this two chamber left sided slice of the heart.  Additionally, the dilation of the pulmonary artery, caused by the diagnosed pulmonary obstruction, can be seen to the right of the image.
This two chamber left sided image shows the dilation of the left atrium as well as a considerable amount of epicardial fat around the ventricles.

The rounded shape of the slightly dilated left ventricle can be seen in this two chamber slice. Additionally, the complexity of the posterior/inferior papillary muscle can be seen to the left of the ventricle.

The left atrium, mitral valve and left ventricular inflow tract can be clearly seen in this two chamber view of the left side.

This left sided two chamber view of the heart clearly shows the left atrium and ventricle separated by the mitral valve.  Interestingly, in this particular specimen the coronary sinus lies closer to the mitral annulus than usual.

The dilated left atrium and the hypertrophic left ventricle are clearly identifiable in this long axis slice, these anatomical variations are often the result of a large left ventricular afterload and possible mitral insufficiency. Part of the left anterior descending artery can be seen, just after branching from the left coronary artery, in the center of the image.

This two chamber right side slice of the heart nicely shows the anterior papillary muscle, it's connection to the anterior leaflet of the tricuspid valve and part of the moderator band to the left of the ventricle.
The two chamber view of the right side shows the large chamber size of the right atrium and the thin walls of both chambers of the right side.

Due to the orientation of the heart in the MR scanner this right two chamber image does not cleanly exhibit the right ventricle.  However, the image does show the trabeculation on the endocardial surface of the right ventricle.

Due to the orientation of the heart in the MR scanner this right two chamber image exaggerates the size of the right atrium in relation to the right ventricle. However, the image does show the thickness of the right ventricular wall and the layer of epicardial fat around the ventricle.
The right side of the heart can be seen in this two chamber long axis slice.
The two chamber view of the right side shows the trabeculation toward the apex of the heart. The dark spots in the image are caused by air pockets in the specimen disrupting the MR image.

Due to the orientation of the heart in the MR scanner this right two chamber image does not cleanly exhibit the right ventricle.  However, the image still shows the trabeculation on the endocardial surface of the right ventricle and the large size of the tricuspid annulus.
The anterior papillary muscle and the anterior and posterior leaflets of the tricuspid valve can be clearly seen in this two chamber long axis view of the right side.
Due to the orientation of the heart in the MR scanner the right side of the heart was not readily imaged.

Delivery Systems - Porcine heart

Electrophysiologic studies require the careful placement of diagnostic electrode catheters within the heart. The use of fluoroscopy and intracardiac EMG recordings verifies the position of the electrode catheters.

Three approaches are generally used for advancing the electrode catheter to the heart: 1) femoral venous approach using the inferior vena cava (IVC); 2) subclavian, jugular, or brachial (antecubital) venous approach via the superior vena cave (SVC); or 3) femoral arterial or retrograde approach via the femoral artery.

The approach chosen depends upon the targeted area within the heart, the number of electrode catheters used during the electrophysiologic study, and physician experience and preference. The femoral arterial approach may also be used for gaining access to the left ventricle and/or left atrium.

As an extension of the IVC approach, an ablation catheter may also be advanced from the right atrium, across the interatrial septum, and into the left atrium using the transseptal approach.

During this approach, the interatrial septum must be punctured before a catheter can be advanced to the left atrium. To create an opening, a transseptal needle is advanced through a long sheath positioned at the foramen ovalis, a thin area of tissue in the interatrial septum. When the needle is withdrawn from the sheath, an ablation catheter is advanced through the septum to the left atrium. At this point the patient must be anticoagulated.

The ablation catheter may then be positioned for mapping and ablation. This approach is useful for left free-wall accessory pathway and AV nodal ablation (atrial fibrillation), as well as future indications for left atrial and left ventricular procedures (e.g., Wolf-Parkinson-White syndrome).

Shown here is a videoscopic view of the transseptal catheterization procedure to access the left atrium through the foramen ovalis (a sheath after a needle puncture).

Delivery Systems - Porcine heart

Electrophysiologic studies require the careful placement of diagnostic electrode catheters within the heart. The use of fluoroscopy and intracardiac EMG recordings verifies the position of the electrode catheters.

Diagnostic Catheters - Porcine heart

Electrophysiologic testing of patients to identify arrhythmias involves intracardiac recording using diagnostic catheters and programmed electrical stimulation of the heart, thus facilitating the diagnoses of bradycardias and tachycardias. Generally, on the right side of the heart, catheters are placed in four locations: high right atrium (HRA), right ventricle (RV), His bundle (His or HB), and the coronary sinus (CS).

Diagnostic catheters are available with fixed curves and deflectable tips.

Cardiac mapping involves the identification of cardiac tissue that is causing the tachycardia. Delivery of radiofrequency current or cryotherapy to create a lesion in the area of interest destroys the selected tissue and prevents arrhythmias.

The HRA catheter is typically placed close to the SA node. The RV catheter is usually positioned in the ventricular apex to record right ventricular activity and for right ventricular pacing. The His bundle catheter is placed across the tricuspid valve to record a His bundle electrogram. A multielectrode catheter is placed in the coronary sinus to record electrical activity in the coronary sinus. Placement of a CS catheter is especially helpful when the arrhythmia mechanism may also involve the left atrium.

Simultaneous use of additional right atrial mapping multielectrode catheters may be used for mapping tachycardias.

Shown here is a videoscopic view of a multi-ring mapping/ablation catheter placed in the high right atrial position which was delivered to the heart via the inferior vena cava.

Simultaneous use of several right heart mapping multielectrode catheters may be used for mapping complex tachycardias.

Therapeutic Catheters - Porcine heart

Not all arrhythmias identified during electrophysiologic studies can be treated by ablation therapy. Often, the mechanism of the arrhythmia determines which treatment will be most successful. The FDA has approved the following indications for radiofrequency (RF) catheter ablation:

  1. atrioventricular nodal reentrant tachycardia (AVNRT);
  2. atrioventricular reentrant tachycardia (AVRT) caused by accessory conduction pathways (also called bypass tracts);
  3. atrioventricular nodal tachycardias resulting in inadequate ventricular rate control;
  4. ventricular tachycardia (VT) occurring in the absence of cardiovascular disease.

This therapy has also been used to treat tachyarrhythmias including:

  1. atrial tachycardia (atrial flutter, atrial fibrillation, and sinus (SA) node reentry);
  2. permanent junctional reciprocating tachycardia (PJRT);
  3. ventricular tachycardia occurring in the presence of structural heart disease.

Shown here is the electrode tip of an ablation catheter positioned along the tricuspid annulus, near the ostium of the coronary sinus. The boundaries of the Triangle of Koch guide catheter placement precisely. As the energy is applied, one can observe a color change in the tissue being ablated.

Shown here is the videoscopic image of an electrode tip of an ablation catheter positioned along the tricuspid annulus, near the ostium of the coronary sinus. As the energy is applied, one can observe a color change in the tissue being ablated. The catheter is moved until the proper lesion is created (e.g., in a line for a linear lesion).

Therapeutic Catheters - Porcine heart

The detection of arrhythmias is a complex process that requires a skilled electrophysiologist so that proper treatment can be provided. Often, the mechanism of the arrhythmia determines which treatment will be most successful.

Shown here is a videoscopic view of an ablation procedure in the right atrium. The inset on the lower right shows electrical signals being recorded (upper signal) as well as left ventricular pressures (lower trace); at times, the heart is being paced through this catheter.

Leads - Canine heart

The pacing lead is a thin insulated wire that carries the electrical impulse to the heart and information about the heart's natural activity back to the pulse generator. One end of the lead is connected to the pulse generator at the connector block. The other end of the lead is connected to the patient, usually inserted through a vein and placed in the right ventricle or the right atrium of the heart.

The tip of the pacing lead may contain a steroid which reduces inflammation and helps maintain a better electrode-tissue electrical interface.

Shown here is a videoscopic view of a lead that was implanted within a heart 33 weeks prior within the right atrial appendage (RAA); one can visualize a fibrous capsule that has formed over the distal portion of the lead body.

Leads - Canine heart

Left Heart Sites - Porcine heart

Pacing from left heart sites has recently been shown to improve cardiac function in patients with advanced heart failure, dilated cardiomyopathy, and ventricular conduction abnormalities. The coronary sinus (CS) vasculature was found to be adequate in most patients (83%) for placement of a LV pacing lead into the posterior-lateral or lateral positions for cardiac resynchronization. Increased tortuosity or lack of an adequate lateral vein resulted in alternative left-sided lead placement in 17% of patients.

Results suggest that LV and RV lead positions are both important in the efficacy of cardiac resynchronization in heart failure patients.

Shown here is a videoscopic view of a left heart lead placed in the great cardiac vein via a delivered catheter positioned within the coronary sinus.

His Bundle - Porcine heart

Pacing the His bundle or near the His bundle may provide for more physiological pacing of the heart, by activating the normal ventricular conduction system. This allows a more rapid and normal activation of the ventricles, i.e., provided that the distal conduction system (right and left bundle branches) is normal. Transvenous His stimulation was demonstrated in canines (1969) and humans (1970) using multipolar catheters positioned at the AV junction above the septal leaflet of the tricuspid valve.

Shown here is a videoscopic view of a lead positioned and implanted to activate the His Bundle.

Coronary Stent - Porcine heart

For more than a decade, vascular stents have been used to treat atherosclerotic lesions in coronary and/or peripheral arteries. Most stents are manufactured from various metal alloys and premounted on a balloon delivery catheter. Self-expanding stents, another fairly common design, are manufactured primarily from Nitinol or stainless steel and protected by a sheath during delivery and deployment. Biodegradable stents are yet another approach being investigated.

Regardless of the design, all stents need to be deliverable, trackable, flexible, conformable, and/or radiopaque (need to be visualized during placement with a given imaging modality). Ideally, a stent placed across a lesion will respect the vessel's natural curvature. Most stents are placed in coronary arteries; other vessels include iliac, renal, and carotid arteries. Physicians access the arteries percutaneously using the femoral, radial, or brachial arteries as the entry point.

Shown here are simultaneous fiberscopic (using Visible Heart methodologies) and fluoroscopic (inset on lower right) views of a stent being deployed in the left anterior descending (LAD) branch of the left coronary artery. First, the balloon with the loaded stent is positioned in the desired location, then the balloon is inflated until the stent is deployed (seen in the fluoroscopic view or continuous X-rays). The fiberscope (2.5 mm, seen as a solid dark line in the fluoroscopic view) is then passed through two deployed stents in the vessel.

Edge-to-Edge Repair (E2E), also known as the "Alfieri stitch" - Porcine heart

Shown here is the normal functioning mitral valve from above or within the left atrium, and then from below or from the left ventricle (one can also see the functional aortic valve to the left). Next, a prolapse of the mitral valve is created by cutting the chordae tendinae of the posterior leaflet (creation of the P2 prolapse). The functional effects of the posterior leaflet are shown from above and then below. Finally, this prolapse is repaired by placing a suture between the A2 and P2 mitral leaflets.

Annuloplasty Ring - Porcine heart

Annuloplasty has been used for more than thirty years to repair and support incompetent mitral and/or tricuspid valves (annuli, or rings). In patients with degenerative heart disease, the surgical placement of a flexible annuloplasty ring is generally preferable to a rigid ring, to subsequently allow the annulus size and configuration to adapt to functional changes that occur throughout the cardiac cycle. It is also considered that a flexible annuloplasty ring permits natural motion of the annulus while preventing annular dilation.

Various techniques are used in mitral and tricuspid valve reconstruction, with the goal of improving valve function (minimizing regurgitation). To perform surgical annuloplasty, the surgeon must expose the valve, make a clinical assessment, and then proceed with the surgical procedure. Additionally, any detectable structural lesions are repaired before surrounding the annulus with the annuloplasty ring to prevent future dilation. Typically such rings are impregnated with barium sulfate, so they can be more easily viewed by echocardiography or X-ray.

Shown here is a videoscopic view from the left atrium of an annuloplasty ring that is surgically placed on the mitral valve annulus.

Mechanical Valve - Human heart 0026

A mechanical valve can be considered as a ring through which blood flows in the heart during desired periods and then closes at appropriate times. Shown here is a bileaflet mechanical valve that was previously surgically implanted in a patient, prior to our laboratory reanimating this heart in vitro. The videoscope is placed within the ascending aorta and directed back towards the heart and the aortic valve. When the mechanical leaflets are open (systole), there is flow through the valve; when they are closed, the ventricle is filling (diastole).

Mechanical Valve - Human heart 0026

Today, mechanical valves are the most common type of valve used to replace the heart's natural valves when they have been damaged, diseased, or weakened by age and no longer adequately control the flow of blood within the heart. A mechanical valve can be considered as a ring through which blood flows in the heart during desired periods and then closes at appropriate times.

Shown here is a bileaflet mechanical valve that was previously surgically implanted in a patient, prior to our laboratory reanimating this heart in vitro. The videoscope is placed through the apex of the left ventricle. The mitral valve is on the right with a Millar pressure catheter (yellow catheter) positioned through it. One can see the aortic valves working, where the mitral is not moving to a great degree; this heart had poor function and was deemed non-viable for transplant.

Mechanical Valve - Porcine heart

Mechanical valves are one type of valve used to replace the heart's natural valves when they have been damaged, diseased, or weakened by age and no longer adequately control the flow of blood within the heart.

A mechanical valve is a ring through which blood flows in the heart; it is made of biocompatible materials such as titanium or carbon. Within the device is a single movable disc or two "leaflets", which open and close much like a natural heart valve.

Mechanical valves are typically used to replace any one of the four valves in the heart. Anticoagulation medication is prescribed for patients with mechanical valves to prevent blood clots.

Shown here is a videoscopic view of a mechanical aortic valve from the left ventricle.

Transcatheter Delivered Pulmonic Valve - Human Heart 048

This new technology is approved for individuals in which a regular valve surgery is not considered a viable option. The valve is loaded into a catheter and placed under fluoroscopic and/or echocardiography visualization. Once properly positioned, the valve is unsheathed and then expanded into position. The leaflets of the Medtronic Melody™ valve are from a bovine jugular valve graft.

Valve comparison - Porcine heart

Shown here is a comparison of two different valves implanted within an isolated swine heart with the native porcine valve (upper left). The implanted valve shown on the upper right is a Medtronic Freestyle® valve; this biologically inert valve is isolated within the native swine aortic tissue. The videoscopic view of the valve in the lower movie clip shows a Medtronic Mosaic® valve that is composed of swine aortic leaflets attached to a sewing ring.

Stentless tissue valve - Porcine heart

A stentless valve is most often an actual heart valve obtained from a human donor (homograft) or a swine (bioprosthesis, xenograft). The porcine aortic valve anatomy closely matches that of humans. Stentless tissue valves are typically used to replace aortic heart valves, and are considered to have viable performance longevity of 10-15 years.

Shown here is a videoscopic view of a stentless bioprosthetic porcine aortic valve that is surgically placed in the aortic position. The videoscope is placed in the ascending aorta and then passed through the valve to obtain a view of the apex of the left ventricle.

This clip was recorded from within the right ventricle. The laser sheath can be seen burning through the fibrosed encapsulation which surrounds the lead body in order to advance toward the implant site. The blue, strobe-like flashing occurs when the laser is in use.
 
[Love CJ, et al.: Novel visualization of intracardiac pacing lead extractions: methodologies performed within isolated canine hearts. Journal of Interventional Cardiac Electrophysiology 24: 27-31, 2009.]

This video image was recorded from within the right atrium. The dilator sheath is completely covering the lead at its implant site in the right atrial wall. The sheath is twisted until the lead is freed and removed from the endocardial surface. Near the end of the clip, another lead, implanted in the right atrial appendage, can be seen in the background.
 
[Love CJ, et al.: Novel visualization of intracardiac pacing lead extractions: methodologies performed within isolated canine hearts. Journal of Interventional Cardiac Electrophysiology 24: 27-31, 2009.]

Recorded from within the right atrium, the radio frequency (RF) sheath can be seen cutting through the fibrosed encapsulation surrounding the lead body. The sheath is rotated around the perimeter of the lead in order to free the lead from the heart wall. The rhythmic, orange flashes of light occur when the device is firing.
 
[Love CJ, et al.: Novel visualization of intracardiac pacing lead extractions: methodologies performed within isolated canine hearts. Journal of Interventional Cardiac Electrophysiology 24: 27-31, 2009.]

This movie demonstrates the direct traction method of removing a lead from the heart wall, as recorded from within the right atrium. The helix of the lead can be seen â€œpullingâ€ at the encapsulation surrounding it. Also seen in this clip, just distal to the lead, is an encapsulation from a previous extraction.
 
[Love CJ, et al.: Novel visualization of intracardiac pacing lead extractions: methodologies performed within isolated canine hearts. Journal of Interventional Cardiac Electrophysiology 24: 27-31, 2009.]

This clip, recorded from within the right atrium, illustrates the level of encapsulation that is left behind on the endocardial surface (in this example, specifically, on the crista terminalis) following a lead extraction procedure.
 
[Love CJ, et al.: Novel visualization of intracardiac pacing lead extractions: methodologies performed within isolated canine hearts. Journal of Interventional Cardiac Electrophysiology 24: 27-31, 2009.]

Shown here is a implantable defibrillator lead (Medtronic 6944) placed within the right ventricle.  The insert on the lower left, shows the electrical sensing by this lead (upper trace, the electrocardiogram) and the relative pressures being generated by the left ventricle within this same heart (lower trace).  Initially a normal sinus rhythm (or heart rate) is being recorded, then the heart is activated by the system/electrode (T-shock) to induce an arrhythmia: i.e., ventricular tachycardia (VT) was induced which subsequently degraded to ventricular fibrillation (VF).  The implanted defibrillator system then continuously was sensing this induced change in the electrical activity of the heart, subsequently and automatically, the system delivered a high energy shock to the heart; which then defibrillated it, and a normal sinus rhythm was re-established.  One should note that during the induce arrhythmia(s), left ventricular pressures essentially went to zero and then subsequently rose when a more normal heart rate was re-established. Note, that such a sequence of events is induced clinically, to to properly set both the sensing and shock voltages of such implantable defibrillator systems.

A view of the cannula that replaced the IVC.  The original IVC was damaged during explant, so a cannula had to be sewn in to provide flow into the right atrium.

Shot of the right ventricular apex.  Note the deep trabeculation of the endocardial surface and the many tendinous conduction chords.  The environment needs to be considered when developing active and passive fixation RV pacing leads.

The right ventricular apex is seen here. There are visible conduction bands that can be seen spaning across the apex. After the close up the camera pans back to see a portion of the moderator band in the upper right corner and a larger view of the apex.

The camera is positioned in the right ventricular outflow tract looking at the inflow tract, particularly the tricuspid valve. Then the camera pans down to see the rest of the inflow tract and backs up and almost completely out of the right ventricular outflow tract.

In this footage the moderator band, a muscular conduction band, can be seen toward the right of the shot connecting the anterior papillary muscle to the septal wall near the posterior papillary muscle of the tricuspid valve.
The moderator band is seen on the right side of the video. In this heart the band is very thick compared to other moderator bands shown on this site.
The anterior papillary muscle as seen from the right ventricle.   The posterior papillary muscle complex can be seen in the background on the right.

In this footage the anterior papillary muscle of the right ventricle can be seen connecting the tricuspid valve, toward the base of the shot, to the ventricular wall.  Note the chordae attaching the valve to the muscle head.

A view of the anterior papillary muscle is seen from above in this video. The papillary muscle looks to be almost bifrucated. In the background conduction bands can be seen, and the muscular tissue that projects to the left attach to the posterior papillary muscle.

The anterior papillary muscle can be seen from within the tricuspid valve. After examining the anterior papilary muscle the camera pans down to inspect the posterior papilary muscle. The chordae tendoneae connections can be seen attaching to the tricuspid valve.
The posterior papillary muscle complex.  There are at least three visible discrete muscles visible.

The posterior papillary muscle of the right ventricle is shown from the papillary muscle head with the chordae attachments to the base.  Note the conduction bands connecting the muscle to the ventricular wall and the unique muscular band stretching from the papillary head to the ventricular wall in the upper left of the shot.

Here the septal papilary complex is shown with the right ventricular outflow tract. The papillary complex is on the right where the chordae attaches to the mycocardium. The pulmonary valve can also be seen in the background where the RVOT leads to.

The tricuspid valve as seen from the right ventricle.  The white bands are chordae tendinae.  The chordae in the foreground on the right side are coming off the septal papillary muscle, the chordae on the left are coming off the anterior papillary muscles, and the chordea intermittently visible in the background on the right are attached to the posterior papillary muscle complex.

An anterior view of the heart in the apparatus. Note the strong atrial contractions and the ventricular fibrillation at the start of the video.  The heart is then defibrillated with an electrical shock through the coil (later removed) causing the atria and ventricles to beat in a coordinated manner. An echo probe is then positioned at the apex to record cardiac ultrasound images.

An anterior view of the heart beating in the apparatus.  Note the light from the endoscopic camera within the right atrium shining through the thin tissue of the atrial free wall.  This heart displays no conduction abnormalities and the pressure generated in the ventricles of the heart are being monitored by the pressure sensors (white wires) exiting the RVOT and the LV apex.

The heart is seen from the anterior. The heart can be seen quivering from dissynchronus myocardial activation. A defibrillation patch over the heart delivers a shock to re-synchronize the heart. Once the shock is delivered the heart remains in asystole until the heart's stretch receptors are activated mechanically. Then the heart regains function and normal contractions.

A view into the right atrial appendage showing the normally "comb" shaped pectinate muscles.  The crista terminalis is the ridge where the the pectinate muscle terminates.

The coronary sinus (center) is bordered by the thebesian valve.  The IVC in the lower right is bordered by ridge referred to as the valve of the IVC or Eustachian valve.  This valve or ridge is thought to help direct blood flow into the foramen ovale during fetal development.

A view of the coronary sinus ostium. The opening in the lower left of the image indicates where the inferior vena cava entered the right atrium. The tricsupid valve is located at the upper right of the image.
A view of the coronary sinus ostium with a Thebesian valve.
A close up view of the coronary sinus ostium from withing the right atrium. A thebesian valve is seen near the ostium.

Showing the crista terminalis, defined as the ridge between the pectinate and smooth muscle inside the right atrium.  The pectinate muscle is seen branching out in the lower half of the image with smooth muscle above it.
A closeup view of the structure where the pectinate muscles terminate, which is called the crista terminalis.

The crista terminalis is pointed out here next to the right atrial free wall. The pectinate muscle is seen here. The thin structure of the right atrial wall is illustrated well with this image, in some cases it is possible to read business cards through the wall of the right atrium due to its thickness.
A view of the free wall of the right atrium. A good view of the pectinate muscle and crista terminalis.
A view of the crista terminalis is shown at the upper right of the image. The pectinate muscle of the right atrial appendage can be seen at the lower left of the image
The crista terminalis is seen here, note how it is very smooth and yet right below the crista terminalis is the free wall of the right atrium that has lots of pectinate muscle on it.
