Here are the primary landmarks of the triangle of koch, the coronary sinus following the eustachian ridge up until it almost intersects the edge of the tricuspid valve then finally returns to the coronary sinus along the edge of the tricuspid valve posterior leaflet.
The triangle of Koch is defined by the tricuspid valve (top), coronary sinus (center in the lower third), and the Eustachian ridge and tendon of Todaro (the continuation of the Eustachian ridge).

Here the tricuspid valve can be seen from the right atrium. The upper most leaflet that is clearly seen in the anterior leaflet of the tricuspid valve and below that is the posterior leaflet. The tricuspid valve is seen from the right atrium. The septal wall is to the lower right hand side of the image and the free wall is to the upper left of the image. Through the valve the right ventricular apex can also be seen.

A closeup view of the right ventricle apex clearly showing the high degree of trabeculations and conduction bands attaching adjoining trabeculae.

A view of the right ventricular apex. The white tissue bands are conduction bands.
Here is the right ventricular apex. White conduction bands can be seen against the walls of the ventricle and they look like white strings connecting various trabeculae.

The moderator can be seen here spanning across the right ventricle. It carries condution fibers within the structure and can transduce a stimulus signal from the septal to the free wall.

The moderator band in the right ventricle connects the septal and free wall.  The band carries conduction fibers from the right bundle branch from the septum and typically connects at or near the base of the anterior papillary muscle.  It is thought that this electrical "shortcut" helps synchronize and coordinate contraction.
A good view of the moderator band in the right ventricle. The anterior papillary muscle can also been seen at the bottom right of the screen.
A view of a moderator band in the right ventricle.
The moderator band is seen here branching from the septal wall. This structure is commonly known for its function to transduce the conduction signal across the ventricle to the free wall.
A view within the right ventricle of a moderator band and trabeculae.

This is a heart with history of mild hypertrophy, and the enlarged shape expresses evidence of this condition.  The ALV is the only vein absent in this heart.  The AIV has 16 main branches, LLV has 2 main branches, PLV has 2 branches, PV has 2 branches, and PIV has 6 main branches.  See the Heart Database for further data.

This is a heart with history of both hypertension and hypertrophy, which can be identified by the rounded curvature of the veins.  The AIV, LLV, 2 PVs, and PIV are present in this heart, and the ALV and PLV are absent.  On the lateral side of the left ventricle, one of the PVs is connected to the LLV.  The AIV has 3 main branches, LLV has 9 main branches, PV 1 has 5 branches, PV 2 has no branches, and PIV has 8 main branches.  See the Heart Database for further data.

This is a heart with cardiac conditions that do not affect the venous anatomy.  The AIV, LLV, 2 PVs, and PIV are present in this heart, and the ALV and PLV are absent.  The AIV has 9 main branches, LLV has 9 branches, PV 1 has 2 branches, PV 2 has 1 branch, and PIV has 4 main branches.  See the Heart Database for further data.

The video shown here starts with the placement of a pulmonary artery catheter (also known as the Swan-Ganz catheter) in a patient in the operating suite. The video then transitions to footage within a reanimated human heart in the Visible Heart Laboratory.

The pulmonary artery (PA) catheter is a highly useful multi-lumen, balloon tipped diagnostic catheter. The balloon on the tip helps to guide the catheter, acting as a ‘sail’ in the flow of blood and also reduces injury to the tissue by acting as a cushion. PA catheters can measure pressures of the heart in multiple chambers of heart, cardiac output via thermodilution, and blood oxygen saturation or tissue oxygen saturation.

The pressure monitoring of the catheter is of particular benefit due to the fact that multiple chambers can be monitored simultaneously. The right atrial, right ventricular, pulmonary artery, and indirect left atrial (‘wedge pressure’) pressures can all be monitored. Due to the fact that there is a pressure lumen distal to the balloon on the tip of the catheter, the catheter can be ‘wedged’ into a small pulmonary artery. When the balloon occludes the artery, the tip sensor is essentially detecting the pressure of the left atria because the lungs are a low resistance path of blood flow. This measurement is particularly useful in assessing fluid status, function of the right and left heart, or the presence of ventricular failure or pulmonary edema to guide therapeutic measures.

A similar video was published in 2012 in the American Journal of Respiratory and Critical Care Medicine titled The Path of a Pulmonary Artery Catheter Visualized through a Beating Human Heart.

Provisional stenting is the generally accepted technique for treatment of bifurcations.   In the video, a stent is used to simulate the provisional technique in treating a bifurcation in a coronary artery.  The main branch is stented first, with the stent deployed to a diameter matching the distal side of the target vessel.  This was then followed by a Proximal Optimization Technique (POT), which addresses the malapposition of stent struts resulting from sizing the stent using the distal side of the target vessel.  Lastly, the use of a final Kissing Balloon Technique (KBT), in which two balloons are simultaneously deployed into the main branch and side branch, is used in order to restore patency to the jailed side branch and obtain better strut apposition at the bifurcation.

For stent deployment, we advanced a guidewire through the left coronary ostium to the left anterior descending artery (LAD). A CordisBx Velocity Rx® balloon expandable stent was advanced over a guidewire to the desired position within the LAD. The balloon was inflated to the manufacturer's recommended pressure and then deflated. The catheter was then withdrawn and the fiberscope, which was positioned distal to the stent, was advanced retrograde through the expanded stent for inspection. This video and description can be found in Eggum JH, Howard SA, Goff RP, & Iaizzo PA. "Imaging of a Coronary Artery Stent Implantation Within an Isolated Human Heart." J Cardiovasc Transl Res. 2012 Feb; 5(1):73-4.

A venogram of human heart 102. A venogram balloon catheter is placed in the coronary sinus. A blue contrast dye is injected into the coronary venous system. The video displays external and fluoroscopic views of the veins. The view begins with an anterior view pans to the left, posterior, right and back to anterior. As the video plays, there is some contrast leakage in the right ventricle seen on fluoroscopy.

A venogram of human heart 109. Two venogram balloon catheters are placed in the coronary sinus and posterior interventricular vein. A blue contrast dye is injected into the coronary venous system. The video displays external and fluoroscopic views of the veins. The view begins with an anterior view pans to the left, posterior, right and back to anterior. In this specimen, many of the right sided anterior veins have collateralization with the posterior internventricular vein.

A venogram of human heart 111. A venogram balloon catheter is placed in the coronary sinus. A blue contrast dye is injected into the coronary venous system. The video displays external and fluoroscopic views of the veins. The view begins with an anterior view pans to the left, posterior, right and back to anterior. The dye is injected more slowly due to air bubble blockages. The anterior interventricular vein is difficult to see on the external view due to a large amount of adipose tissue.

A venogram of human heart 118. A venogram balloon catheter is placed in the coronary sinus. A blue contrast dye is injected into the coronary venous system. The video displays external and fluoroscopic views of the veins. The view begins with an antero-lateral view and pans to the left, posterior, right and back to anterior. There is collateralization between the right marginal vein and mid-posterior interventricular vein. Some pooling of the constrast can be seen in the right ventricle on fluoroscopy.

A venogram of human heart 132. A venogram balloon catheter is placed in the coronary sinus. A blue contrast dye is injected into the coronary venous system. The video displays external and fluoroscopic views of the veins. The view begins with a posterior view. Unlike the rest of the great cardiac veins, the posterior interventricular vein is filled antegrade by the dye. The heart is rotated from the posterior view to the right to the anterior to the left and back to the original view.

A venogram of human heart 136. A venogram balloon catheter is placed in the coronary sinus. A blue contrast dye is injected into the coronary venous system. The video displays external and fluoroscopic views of the veins. The view begins with a left lateral view and rotates to the posterior side of the specimen. The posterior interventricular vein is filled antegrade half-way. The specimen continues to rotate to its right and anterior side.

A venogram of human heart 134. A venogram balloon catheter is placed in the coronary sinus. A blue contrast dye is injected into the coronary venous system. The video displays external and fluoroscopic views of the veins. The view begins with a right lateral view and rotates to the anterior side of the specimen. Some of the anterior interventricular vein and great cardiac vein are covered by adispose tissure in the external view. The specimen continues to rotate, which provides a good view of the coronary veins on the left ventricle.

A venogram of human heart 146. A venogram balloon catheter is placed in the coronary sinus. A blue contrast dye is injected into the coronary venous system. The video displays external and fluoroscopic views of the veins. The view begins with a postero-lateral view and rotates to the posteior side of the specimen. The posterior/inferior vein of the left ventricle and the posterior interventricular vein fill immediately. The heart does a 360 rotation and ends with good posterior view of the coronary veins.

A venogram of human heart 138. A venogram balloon catheter is placed in the coronary sinus. A blue contrast dye is injected into the coronary venous system. The video displays external and fluoroscopic views of the veins. The view begins with a left lateral view and rotates to the posteior side of the specimen. The left lateral vein fills immediately and the posterior interventricular vein is slowly filled antegrade. The heart does a 360 rotation and ends with good view of the left lateral vein.

A venogram of human heart 126. A venogram balloon catheter is placed in the coronary sinus. A blue contrast dye is injected into the coronary venous system. The video displays external and fluoroscopic views of the veins. The view begins with an anterior view and rotates to the left side of the specimen, provides a nice view of the 2 major left lateral veins. The view continues to rotate to the posterior side of the specimen where the posterior/inferior vein of the left ventricle and the posterior internventricular vein are slowly filling antegrade. On the right side, several anterior veins are filled antegrade from collateralizations from the great cardiac veins.

A venogram of human heart 139. A venogram balloon catheter is placed in the coronary sinus. A blue contrast dye is injected into the coronary venous system. The video displays external and fluoroscopic views of the veins. The view begins with a left lateral view where two left lateral veins are filled with the dye. The view continues to rotate to the posterior side of the specimen where the posterior internventricular vein is filling antegrade.

A venogram of human heart 98. A venogram balloon catheter is placed in the coronary sinus. A blue contrast dye is injected into the coronary venous system. The video displays external and fluoroscopic views of the veins. The view begins with a antero-lateral view and rotates posteriorly, which provides a good view of the posterior/inferior vein of the left ventricle and the posterior interventricular. The small cardiac vein is quite large on this specimen and can also be seen wrapping around the right atrioventricular groove.

A venogram of human heart 128. A venogram balloon catheter is placed in the coronary sinus. A blue contrast dye is injected into the coronary venous system. The video displays external and fluoroscopic views of the veins. The view begins with a antero-lateral view, which provides a good view of a large antero-lateral vein that fills immediately. As the heart rotates posteriorly, the posterior/inferior vein of the left ventricle and posterior interventricular vein fill antegrade. The veins on the left side are well visualized considering the large amount of adipose tissue.

A venogram of human heart 127. A venogram balloon catheter is placed in the coronary sinus. A blue contrast dye is injected into the coronary venous system. The video displays external and fluoroscopic views of the veins. The view begins with a lateral view, which provides a good view of a left lateral vein that fills immediately. As the heart rotates posteriorly, the posterior/inferior vein of the left ventricle and posterior interventricular vein fill antegrade.

A venogram of human heart 140. A venogram balloon catheter is placed in the coronary sinus. A blue contrast dye is injected into the coronary venous system. The video displays external and fluoroscopic views of the veins. The view begins with a posterior view, where the CS and left lateral veins fill immediately. A view of the aortic valve from within the aortic root. When the left ventricle relaxes during diastole, flow of blood back into the left ventricle is prevented by the aoric semilunar valve. The three cusps of the valve are anchored to the fibrous skeleton within the root of the aorta.

A view of the ascending aorta which carries the oxygenated blood from the left ventricle to rest fo the body. A closed aortic semilunar valve is seen in this image. The aortic valve will be closed during diastole, when the ventricles of the heart are filling with blood.

A close-up view of the left coronary artery ostium, located in close proximity to the cusps of the aortic valve. During diastole the cusps of the aortic valve close up allowing for distention of the aortic wall and pressurized filling coronary arteries. Thsi allows oxygenated blood to be sent to the myocardium tissue of the heart.
Close-up view of the coronary sinus ostium from within the right atrium. The coronary sinus returns deoxygenated blood used by the myocardial tissue back to the right side of the heart.

View of the foramen ovale from within the left atrium. During fetal development this area of the interatrial septum remains open allowing for flow of blood from the right to the left atrium, therefore bypassing the under-developed lungs.
View of the mitral valve from above. The mirtal valve closes during systole as blood is pumped from the left ventricle to the peripherals of the body.
View of the left pulmonary vein ostia from within the left atrium which returns oxygenated blood from the left lung back into the left side of the heart.
View of a closed off right pulmonary vein, returning oxygenated blood from the right lung back to the left side of the heart.

A close-up view of the body of the anterior papillary muscle and associated chordae tendineae which extend superiorly to attach to the anterior leaflet of the mitral valve. The anterior papillary muscle helps prevent prolapse of the mitral valve into the left ventricle.

View of the outflow track of the left ventricle. The aortic valve is seen in its closed state as the three leaflets of the semilunar valve press against each other during diastole to prevent backflow into the left side of the heart.
View of the apex of the left ventricle which aids in the pumping of the blood from the left ventricle to the aorta.

Beyond the cusp of the mitral valve, the free wall of the left ventricle can be seen. The free wall is composed of trabeculae carneae, thick but fine muscular bundles which aid in the contraction of the left ventricle.

A view of the smooth surface of the interventricular septum. This septum separates the two ventricular chambers of the heart and appears from within the left ventricle to buldge into the right ventricle.
Ventricle bands can be seen connecting muscle bundles of the trabeculae carneae. These bands aid in the coordination of contraction within the left ventricle.
The posterior papillary muscle of the left ventricle pictured here with the associated chordae tendineae extending superiorly to attach to the posterior leaflet of the mitral valve.
Close-up view of an open pulmonary valve from within the pulmonary artery. The semilunar pulmonary valve opens during systole to allow blood flow from the right ventricle to the lungs.

A view of the coronary sinus ostium from within the chamber of the right atium. The Thesbian valve is partially seen to be covering the coronary sinus, which prevents backflow of blood into the coroanry sinus.
View of the crista terminalis from within the right atrium. The crista terminalis is a smooth ridge separating the pectinate muscle and appendage from the smooth wall of the atrium.

View of the ovale shaped foramen ovalis from the right atrium. The foramen ovalis remains patent during fetal development to shunt blood from the right to the left atrium thereby bypassing the developing lungs. The foramen ovalis is part of the interatrial septum.
View of the opening of the inferior vena cava from the right atrium. The inferior vena cava returns deoxygenated blood from the inferior body back to the right heart.

View of the interatrial septum from the right atrium. The smooth surface of septumdevelops during the first and second months of fetal development. Atrial septal defects are a common heart malformation occurring when the interatrial septum fails to properly close in development.
View of the lateral wall of the right atrium. The pectinate muscles of the wall help in contraction of the chamber during diastole.

The Triangle of Koch is defined spatially by the coronary sinus ostium, anterior border of the tricuspid valve, and the Eustachian ridge. The triangle of Koch is used to approximate the location of the AV node.
A close-up view of the tricuspid valve from the right atrium. The three leaflets of the valve can be seen - anterior, posterior, and septal.

A view of the anterior papillary muscle from within the right ventricle. The anterior papillary is found along the free wall of the ventricle and attaches to the anterior leaflet of the tricuspid valve through chordae tendineae.
View of the right ventricular apex. The apex aids in pumping of blood from the ventricle to pulmonary artery.

A view of the moderator band in the right ventricle connecting the septal wall to the anterior papillary muscle. The moderator band aids in conduction and coordination of contraction of the papillary muscles within the right ventricle.

A view of the right ventricular outflow tract from the right ventricle. The outflow track leads to the pulmonic valve, seen here in its open configuration, which serves as a gate to the pulmonary artery.
A view of the posterior papillary muscle. The muscle is seen extending from the posterior wall of the chamber and attaching to the posterior leaflet of the tricuspid valve.
A close-up view of the pulmonary valve from the right ventricle. The pulmonary valve is open as it would be during systole.

Close-up view of the septal papillary muscle found along the septal wall of the right ventricle. This papillary muscle attaches to the septal leaflet of the tricuspid valve through its associated chordae tendineae.

A view of an open tricuspid valve from below. All three papillary muscle of the right ventricle are seen attaching to their respective leaflets on the tricuspid valve. The tricuspid valve opens during diastole and closes during systole.

Provisional stenting is the generally accepted technique for treatment of bifurcations.   In the video, a stent is used to simulate the provisional technique in treating a bifurcation in a coronary artery.  The main branch is stented first, with the stent deployed to a diameter matching the distal side of the target vessel.  This was then followed by a Proximal Optimization Technique (POT), which addresses the malapposition of stent struts resulting from sizing the stent using the distal side of the target vessel.  Lastly, the use of a final Kissing Balloon Technique (KBT), in which two balloons are simultaneously deployed into the main branch and side branch, is used in order to restore patency to the jailed side branch and obtain better strut apposition at the bifurcation.

In this video a main branch coronary artery was stented and a side branch vessel was opened (provisional technique).  Next, a side-branch stent was crossed into the branch and then placed (balloon inflated to expand stent): wires are still placed and visible in each branch.

Transcatheter Leadless Pacemaker - Human Heart 0216

Multimodal imaging of a transcatheter pacemaker implantation within a reanimated human heart

With the development of transcatheter pacemakers, new transcatheter delivery systems and implantation techniques are also necessary. In order to further understand the interaction of a transcatheter pacing system (TPS) with functional anatomy and to provide important insights into the device-tissue interface, a transcatheter pacemaker was implanted in a reanimated human heart using both direct visualization and fluoroscopy.

This video was originally published in Heart Rhythm, and is made available here with their permission.

CoreValve Implantation - Human Heart 0136

Multimodal Imaging of a Transcatheter Aortic Valve Implantation Within an Isolated Heart

NOVEL IMAGING OF FUNCTIONAL CARDIAC ANATOMY is possible in isolated heart preparations when a clear perfusate is used; which, in turn, provides important insights into the device-tissue interface of implanted devices such as transcatheter valves. The implantation of a transcatheter aortic valve (TAV) (CoreValve System, Medtronic, Inc., Mounds View, Minnesota) within an isolated human heart was performed using echocardiography, fluoroscopy, and direct visualization to compare imaging modalities for better understanding of the implantation procedure.

This video was originally published in JACC: Cardiovascular Imaging, and is made available here with their permission.

Following a transseptal puncture of the fossa ovalis, the pulmonary vein is cannulated with a guidewire. The delivery catheter containing the cryoablation balloon is advanced to the left inferior pulmonary vein. The balloon is inflated and positioned in the pulmonary vein ostia. Cryoablation starts and initiates ice formation/cell death. After the 4 minute ablation, the thaw process begins and the balloon is deflated when it warms up to 20°C. Subsequently, the catheter is removed from the pulmonary vein of interest.

A close-up view of the bands of the left ventricle attaching directly to a papillary muscle.
A close-up view of the free wall of the left ventricle. Note the high degree of trabeculation as well as the Anterior Papillary muscle and attached chordae tendoneae.

View of the posterior papillary complex showing how the trabeculation of the left ventricular free wall often integrates with the papillary complex. Towards the end of the video clip the chordae tendoneae can be seen which attach the papillary muscle to the posterior leaflet of the mitral valve.
A view of the pulmonary valve from the pulmonary trunk. The Anterior cusp is located on the top of the screen with the right cusp and left cusp respectively moving clockwise.

A close-up view of the coronary sinus ostium. A posterior interventricular vein ostium can be seen branching off just inside the coronary sinus ostium. Not the Coronary sinus contracting with the right atrium.

A close-up view of the right atrial appendage. The tricuspid valve is seen in the lower left corner of the screen. The sagittal band can be seen extending from the top left corner and branching into many smaller pectinate muscles.
A view of the fossa ovalis from the right atrium. Note the abnormal chord like structures around the rim. As the atria contract the fossa can be seen bulging into the right atrium.

A close-up view of the right atrial appendage. The tricuspid valve is seen in the lower left corner of the screen. The sagittal band can be seen extending from the top left corner and branching into many smaller pectinate muscles.

A view of the intra-arterial septum as seen from the Superior Vena Cava. The fossa ovalis is on the left of the screen with then canulated inferior vena cava ostium on the right. The coronary sinus is also viewed in the upper left portion of the screen.

A close-up view of the triangle of Koch. The septal leaflet of the Tricuspid Valve (top of screen) forms one side with the Coronary Sinus Ostium (bottom right) and Eustachian ridge (bottom left) forming the other two borders.
A view of the tricuspid valve from the right atrium. The septal leaflet is seen to the bottom left with the Anterior leaflet on the top right and the posterior leaflet on the bottom right.

Right ventricular anterior papillary muscle. Here the endoscope is placed through the pulmonary valve, with the chordae tendoneae seen attaching the papillary muscle to the anterior leaflet of the Tricuspid Valve.
A close-up view of the right ventricle apex. Note the high degree of trabeculation and conduction bands present. Small yellow fat deposits an also be seen buried within the trabeculeae.

A view of the moderator band of the right ventricle. The moderator band attaches the interventricular septum to the  anterior papillary muscle. The tricuspid valve is located just off the right of the screen.

A view of the right ventricle outflow tract (RVOT) as seen by a camera placed through the tricuspid valve and looking upward towards the pulmonary valve. At the beginning of the video we see RV apex and the extreme low portion of the RVOT. The camera then advances and angels towards the pulmonary valve.

A view of the pulmonary valve from the right ventricle being visualized by a scope placed through the tricuspid valve. The Anterior Cusp is located in the top right corner, with the Left Cusp and Right Cusp respectively when moving clockwise. The Septal papillary muscle and septal leaflet of the tricuspid can also be seen on the bottom half of the screen.

A close-up view of the septal papillary muscle visualized by an endoscope placed through the pulmonary valve. The chordae can be seen going from the papillary muscle to the septal leaflet of the tricuspid valve.
View of the left coronary artery ostia. The left cusp of the aortic valve is visible on the upper left portion of the image.
View of the right coronary ostia where the right coronary cusp is located to the upper right portion of the screen. A pigtail catheter can be seen in the lower left corner of the video.
View of the coronary sinus ostium and the thebesian valve. The tricuspid valve annulus is visible in the upper right portion of the screen along with the septal leaflet of the tricuspid valve.

Fossa Ovalis imaged simultaneously from the left atrium (top left), right atrium (top right), echo (bottom left), and fluoroscopy (bottom right). Notice the large amount of movement in the fossa as the atria contract, this can lead to difficulty maintaining location during transseptal punctures.

Here the mitral valve is visualized directly via an endoscope placed through the LV apex (top left), via echo (bottom left), and using fluoroscopy (bottom right). The posterior leaflet is located on the upper part of the image, while the anterior leaflet is towards the bottom.

Pulmonary valve as viewed from the pulmonary trunk (upper left) and right ventricular outflow tract (upper right). An echo view of the valve is visible (bottom left) and a fluoroscopic view (bottom right) in an anterior-posterior plane.

Tricuspid valve viewed using 4 imaging modalities simultaneously: a camera in the right atrium (top left) and ventricle (top right), echo (bottom left) and fluoroscopy (bottom right). A mapping catheter is placed at the level of the annulus to better visualize the location on fluoroscopy.
External view of the heart and lungs from the anterior surface. Note the high degree of fat buildup on the epicardial surface of the heart.
Fossa Ovalis is viewed from the left atrium. Notice the large amount of movement in the fossa as the atria contract, this can lead to difficulty maintaining location during transseptal punctures.
View of the left ventricular anterior papillary muscle. Note the number of chordae leaving the papillary to attach to the mitral valve.

View of the left ventricular apex from the tricuspid valve. Many conduction and LV bands are present through the ventricle as well as a high degree of trabeculations. Also note the arrhythmia of contractions as the heart beats normally, skips a few beats, and then begins contracting again.

View of the interventricular septum from the left ventricle. The anterior leaflet of the mitral valve can be seen attaching to the anterior papillary muscle. There is a large amount of calcium deposits on the leaflets of the mitral valve.

Here the mitral valve is imaged via an endoscope passed through the left ventricular apex. The posterior leaflet is located on the upper part of the image, while the anterior leaflet is towards the bottom.

View of the posterior papillary muscle attaching to the mitral valve. The anterior leaflet is along the top of the valve and the posterior leaflet is along the bottom. Note the yellow colored deposits on the leaflets of the valve.

View of the pulmonary from the pulmonary trunk. The ring of a cannula used to attach the heart to the apparatus is visible around the outer portion of the video. The anterior cusp is located on the bottom right, the right cups is on the left, and the left cusp is along the top.
View of the right atrial appendage from the superior vena cava. There is a large number of papillary muscles stretching throughout the appendage.
View of the coronary sinus ostium and the thebesian valve. The canulated inferior vena cava ostium is located in the lower right portion of the image (white).

View of the crista terminalis from the superior vena cava. The pectinate muscle of the right atrial appendage can be seen extending out from the crista terminalis. At the end of the video the tricuspid valve and annulus can be seen on the right portion of the image.
Fossa Ovalis is viewed from the right atrium. Notice the large amount of movement in the fossa as the atria contract, this can lead to difficulty maintaining location during transseptal punctures.

View of the inferior vena cava (IVC) ostium from the superior vena cava. The IVC has been canulated to allow for re-animation of the heart. The Eustachian ridge can be seen extending the  upper left portion of the IVC to the left side of the picture. The coronary sinus ostium and thebesian valve are also visible in the upper left corner of the image.
View of the Tricuspid Valve from the right atrium. The anterio leaflet is located along the left of the image, with the posterior leaflet on the top, and the septal leaflet on the bottom right.
View of the anterior papillary muscle attaching to the tricuspid valve. Note that the anterior papillary muscle divides into three separate heads which then attach to the chordae tendoneae.
A straight down view of the posterior papillary muscle in the right ventricle. Not the numerous locations where the chordae tendoneae attach to the structure.
View of the right ventricular outflow tract from the RV apex. The septal papillary muscle and the tricuspid valve are seen at the bottom.

View of the posterior papillary complex in the right ventricle from the tricuspid valve. The papillary branches into several components which then attaches to the chordae tendoneae before attaching to the posterior leaflet of the tricuspid valve.

View of the septal papillary muscle from the tricuspid valve. The septal papillary muscle is a small muscular structure which then attaches to the chordae tendoneae and the septal leaflet of the tricuspid valve.

Aortic Valve as viewed from inside the ascending aorta. The non-coronary cusp is located at the top of the screen with the left coronary cusp in the bottom right and right coronary cusp in the bottom left. Note the high degree of calcification on the cusps of the valve.
View of the right coronary artery ostium. Note the calcium deposits surrounding the ostium.
View of the left coronary arteria ostia. Note that there are three distinct ostia, which differs from the typical single ostium, as can be seen in the left coronary artery footage for this heart.

Functional view of the aortic valve using two endoscopes, one placed in the ascending aorta (top left) and one through the left ventricular apex (top right), echo (bottom left), and fluoroscopy (bottom right). On fluoroscopy you can visualize the location of the cameras and the echo probe in relation to the heart.

Functional view of the mitral valve imaged using an endoscope in the left atrium (top left), and endoscope through the left ventricular apex (top right), 2-chamber long axes echo (bottom left) and fluoroscopy (bottom right).

Functional view of the pulmonary valve using an endoscope one placed in the pulmonary artery (top left) and one through the tricuspid valve angled back to the right ventricular outflow tract (top right), echo (bottom left), and fluoroscopy (bottom right). A mapping catheter has been placed through the pulmonary valve to better visualize the level of the annulus on fluoroscopy.

Functional view of the tricuspid valve using an endoscope one placed in the right atrium (top left) and one through the pulmonary valve angled back to the right ventricular inflow tract (top right), echo (bottom left), and fluoroscopy (bottom right). A mapping catheter has been placed through the valve to better visualize the level of the annulus on fluoroscopy.

External view of the heart fibrillating prior to re-animation. This video was taken less than 1 minute after a the heart was given 1500ug of dobutamine. The dobutamine causes an increase in contraction rate and the strength of the contractions.

Functional view of the exterior surface of the heart. Left ventricular apex is pointing directly towards the camera. There are pressure catheters visible extending from left ventricular apex and the right ventricular outflow tract. A pad to be used for external cardioversion is also visible on the right atrium.

Functional view of the exterior surface of the heart. The right atrial appendage is at the top of the screen and has very little fat (yellow). A camera can be seen lighting the appendage from inside of the heart demonstrating how thin the tissue is.
Fossa Ovalis as viewed from the left atrium. The thin nature of the fossa is demonstrated by placing a light in the right atrium and it can be visualized through the fossa ovalis.
View of the left atrial appendage as seen through the right pulmonary veins. Note that the left atrial appendage is both smaller and appears thicker than the right atrial appendage.

View of the mitral valve from the left atrium. The anterior leaflet is located on the bottom/right of the image while the posterior leaflet is located on the left of the valve. The valve is lit by a camera placed in the left ventricle through the apex.

View of the right pulmonary vein ostia. The superior ostium is located at the top of the image. As the video progresses the right inferior pulmonary vein ostium comes into view at the bottom left of the screen. The fossa ovlais is also visible on the right of the image.

View of the left pulmonary vein ostia. The left superior pulmonary vein ostium is located in the bottom right portion of the screen while the inferior pulmonary vein ostium is located in the top right. The mitral valve is also visible in the top left corner and left atrial appendage is in the bottom middle of the image.

Functional view of the anterior papillary complex in the left ventricle. Note that the complex is made of a single muscle that separates into two distinct heads which then attach to the chordae tendoneae.

View of the aortic valve from an endoscope placed through the left ventricular apex. The right coronary cusp is located in the bottom right of the image, with the left coronary cusp and non-coronary cusp respectively clockwise.

View of the left ventricular apex from a camera placed through the mitral valve. There is a large amount of trabeculation throughout the apex. Also note the amount of contraction that the apex experiences with each contraction of the heart.

View of the left ventricular bands in the apex from a camera placed through the mitral valve. There is a large amount of trabeculation throughout the apex. Also note the amount of contraction that the apex experiences with each contraction of the heart.
View of the mitral valve from the left ventricular apex. The anterior leaflet is on the right and the posterior leaflet is on the left. The aortic valve is also visible at the far right of the image.
View of the posterior papillary complex from the mitral valve. The papillary extends from the apex towards the camera before bifurcating into three separate heads.

View of the pulmonary valve from the pulmonary trunk. A pressure catheter can be seen in the right ventricular outflow tract directly behind the anterior cusp of the pulmonary valve. The right cusp is located on the bottom left of the screen and the left cusp is on the top left.

View of the coronary sinus ostium and the thebesian valve. The thebesian valve is the thin white tissue that covers the opening of the ostium. As the video progresses the Septal and anterior leaflets of the tricuspid valve are visible in the lower right corner.

View of the crista terminalis and the right atrial appendage. The crista terminalis is the smooth ridge that separates the pectinate muscle of the appendage from the smoother muscle of the atrium (top right).  This video also demonstrates how thin the tissue of the appendage is as a business card is passed over the outer surface and the "University of Minnesota" is clearly visualized through the tissue.

View of the right atrial appendage fibrillating before whole heart reanimation. The pathway of conduction can be seen propagating through the tissue and the changing as beats are triggered from various locations throughout the atrial appendage.

View of the crista terminalis and the right atrial appendage. The crista terminalis is the smooth ridge that separates the pectinate muscle of the appendage from the smoother muscle of the atrium (top right).  This video also demonstrates how thin the tissue of the appendage is as a business card is passed over the outer surface and the "University of Minnesota" is clearly visualized through the tissue.
Tricuspid Valve as viewed from the right atrium. The septal leaflet is located on the left of the screen with the anterior leaflet in the top right and the posterior leaflet on the bottom right.

View of the anterior papillary muscle of the tricuspid valve.  Several conduction bands can be seen extending perpendicular to the papillary muscle while the chordae tendoneae extend out the top of the papillary and eventually connect to the tricuspid valve leaflets.
View of the right ventricular apex. There is a large amount of trabeculation that can be seen throughout the apex. There are also a large number of conduction bands throughout the apex.
View of the right ventricular inflow tract from an endoscope placed through the pulmonary valve. The septal leaflet is visible on the lower portion of the screen.

View of the moderator band the  right ventricle. The intraventricular septum is seen on the left and the moderator (thick muscular band) is seen connecting to the base of the anterior papillary muscle on the right of the screen.

View of the right ventricular outflow tract from an endoscope placed through the tricuspid valve, then angled back towards the pulmonary valve. The septal papillary muscle is viewed on the middle right portion of the screen and the pulmonary valve is in the top right corner.

View of the septal papillary muscle. The septal papillary muscle is much smaller than the anterior or posterior papillary muscle and is located right at the base of the right ventricular outflow tract.

Tricuspid valve as viewed from the right ventricular outflow tract. The septal papillary muscle is in the front of this image (top), while the anterior papillary (bottom) and attaches directly to the anterior leaflet of the tricuspid valve. The posterior leaflet and papillary are visible in the background of the image.

A 3D reconstruction of the blood volume of heart 0046 is visualized here. The right side volume is modeled in blue, and the left side is modeled in red. The proximal portions of the right and left coronary arteries are visible. The cusps of the pulmonary valve are aslo seen in the blue mask.

This is a 3D reconstruction of the tissue and blood volume for Heart 0046.  In the blood volume mask the right and left blood volumes are seen along with proximal portions of the coronary sinus and coronary arteries. The tissue mask is overlayed to provide a reference to overall heart shape and size.

This is a 3D blood volume reconstruction of a heart from a 25 year old male. In this reconstruction one can clearly visualize the shape of the left and right atrial appendages, along with the right ventricular outflow tract.

This is a 3D tissue and blood volume reconstruction of a heart from a 25 year old male. In this reconstruction one can clearly visualize the shape of the left and right atrial appendages, along with the right ventricular outflow tract. The tissue mask is overlayed to provide a reference for overall heart shape and size.

Shown is a 3D reconstruction of a heart from a 47 year old female with PAD and chronic hypertension.  The pulmonary valve can be visualized via indentations in the right side (blue) blood volume mask. The amount of trabeculation can also be seen in both the left and right ventricular blood volumes.

Shown is a 3D reconstruction of a heart from a 47 year old female with PAD and chronic hypertension.  The pulmonary valve can be visualized via indentations in the right side (blue) blood volume mask. The amount of trabeculation can also be seen in both the left and right ventricular blood volumes. The tissue is overlayed to show the degree of left ventricular wall thinkening and provide a reference for overall size and shape.

This is a 3D blood volume reconstruction of the heart of a 73 year old female with a history of Atrial Fibrillation. The aortic valve is prominently fratured in this model and its location is marked via indentations in the left (red) sided blood volume.

This is a 3D blood and tissue volume reconstruction of the heart of a 73 year old female with a history of Atrial Fibrillation. The aortic valve is prominently fratured in this model and its location is marked via indentations in the left (red) sided blood volume.  The overlayed tissue mask shows a large degree of left ventricular wall thinkening.

Shown here is a 3D blood volume reconstruction of a heart from a 61 year old female. The left atrium of this heart has been removed likely due to lung transplantation. The aortic valve is prominently featured in this model and its location is marked via indentations in the left (red) sided blood volume.

Shown here is a 3D blood volume reconstruction of a heart from a 61 year old female. The left atrium of this heart has been removed likely due to lung transplantation. The aortic valve is prominently featured in this model and its location is marked via indentations in the left (red) sided blood volume. The tissue mask is overlayed to provide a reference for overall heart shape and size.
This is a 3D tissue reconstruction of a heart from a 25 year old male. This individual had an extensive history of drug and alcohol abuse however their cardiac history was relatively normal.

This video shows a 3D reconstruction of a heart generated from a CT scan. The heart is from a 50 year old male with hypertension, hypercholesterolemia, and a 25 year smoking history. In this reconstruction the right ventricular outflow tract (RVOT) is prominently featured extenind across the anterior surface of the heart.

Shown below is a 3D reconstruction of a heart from a 47 year old female with PAD and chronic hypertension.  The aorta and superior vena are prominently featured in this reconstruction. A band of fat can also be seen covering the coronary sinus as it wraps around the left atrium. Another prominent feature of this heart is the single common left pulmonary vein.

This is a 3D reconstruction of the heart of a 73 year old female with a history of Atrial Fibrillation. The Inferior Vena Cava ostium on the posterior surface of the hearts allows us to see a marker placed at thelevel of the Tricuspid valve annulus.

Shown here is a 3D reconstruction of a heart from a 61 year old female. The left atrium of this heart hasa been removed likely due to lung transplantation. Because the left atrium is not present the Mitral Valve is easily visible as the heart rotates.

Blood volume model from a 51 year old male with a history of hypertension. The blood volume of the left atrial appendage is nicely reconstructed here.

Combined blood and tissue model from a 51 year old male with a history of hypertension. The transpartent tissue model allows visualization of the wall thickness, note how the RV and LV wall thinkness is very similar in this particular heart.
Combined blood and tissue model from a 51 year old male with a history of hypertension. The coronary vasculature is visible on the anterior surface of this 3D reconstruction.
Shown here is a blood volume  model of Heart0083 from a 56 year old male with no known cardiac history.  This model shows a slight degree of left ventricular hypertrophy.
Shown here is a combined blood and tissue  model of Heart0083 from a 56 year old male with no known cardiac history.  This model shows a slight degree of left ventricular hypertrophy.

This model represents the combined blood and tissue  model of Heart0096 from a 54 year old male with a history of hypertension and semilunar valve regurgitation. This shows the bifrication of the pulmonary artery in the blue, or right side, blood volulme.

This model represents the combined blood and tissue  model of Heart0096 from a 54 year old male with a history of hypertension and semilunar valve regurgitation. The left atrium and pulmonary veins are visualized in this model.
This model represents the blood model of Heart0110 from a 61 year old female with no known cardiac history. All three of the branches off the aortic arch are visible in this model.

This model represents the combined blood and tissue model of Heart0110 from a 61 year old female with no known cardiac history. The increased thickness of the left ventricular wall is nicely reconstructed here.
Shown here is a blood model of Heart0141 from a 24 year old female with no known cardiac history. This model is an accurate representation of an approximately normal heart.
Shown here is a combined blood and tissue model of Heart0141 from a 24 year old female with no known cardiac history. This model is an accurate representation of an approximately normal heart.

Shown here is a blood model of Heart0145 from a 53 year old male with no known cardiac history. The proximal portion of the coronary sinus is reconstructed here. The blood volume of the left atrium is nicely recomstructed.

Shown here is a combined blood and tissue model of Heart0145 from a 53 year old male with no known cardiac history. The left ventricular blood volume and wall thickness are an accurate representation of an average heart.
This model represents the blood model of Heart0157 from a 78 year old female with no known cardiac history. The coronary arteries and their proximal branches are nicely visualized here.

This model represents the combined blood and tissue model of Heart0157 from a 78 year old female with no known cardiac history.The coronary artries can be seen extending from the just about the susps of the aortic valve.
Shown here is a blood model of Heart0215 from a 57 year old female with a 40+ year smoking history and COPD. This is an accurate representation of an approximately normal heart.

Shown here is a combined blood and tissue model of Heart0215 from a 57 year old female with a 40+ year smoking history and COPD. This model nicely visualizes the differences in wall thickness between the left and right ventricles. Note the thinkness of the right ventricle can be increased due to high pulmonary resistance.

Shown here is a blood model of Heart0229 from a 44 year old female with a history of hypertension. The left ventricular volume is not significantly decreased, contrary to what is normally seen in patients with hypertension.
Shown here is a combined tissue and blood model of Heart0229 from a 44 year old female with a history of hypertension. The left ventricular wall is slightly thicker than normal.
Shown here is a tissue model of Heart0083 from a 56 year old male with no known cardiac history.  This model represents an approximately normal tissue model with slight left ventricular hypertrophy.

This model represents the tissue  model of Heart0096 from a 54 year old male with a history of hypertension and semilunar valve regurgitation. The left and right atria shown in this model are an accurate representation for an approximately normal heart.
This model represents the tissue model of Heart0110 from a 61 year old female with no known cardiac history. The model is an accurate representation of an approximately normal heart.

Shown here is a tissue model of Heart0141 from a 24 year old female with no known cardiac history. There is a layer of fat surrounding the coronary sinus which can be seen on the posterior surface of the heart.
Shown here is a tissue model of Heart0145 from a 53 year old male with no known cardiac history. A slight depression is visible in the pulmonary artery, which probably occurred during plastination.

This model represents the tissue model of Heart0157 from a 78 year old female with no known cardiac history. A large amount of epicardial fat accounts for the distortion around the superior vena cava and pulmonary artery.

Shown here is a tissue model of Heart0215 from a 57 year old female with no known cardiac history. Both branches of the pulmonary artery are visible in this model. Note the thinkness of the right ventricle and right ventricular outflow tract can be increased due to high pulmonary resistance.
Shown here is a tissue model of Heart0229 from a 44 year old female with a history of hypertension. All four pulmonary veins can be seen on the posterior surface of the left atrium.
